Hey Victor - what's the reason for changing the mocked out os.path.exists?  It seemed reasonable to me the way it was before with the exists getting mocked out with a False or True in each test case."}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-11-10 09:45:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ryan McNair: "Hey Victor - what's the reason for changing the mocked out os.path.exists? It seemed reasonable to me the way it was before with the exists getting mocked out with a False or True in each test case."

On Python 3, the import machinery is now implemented in Python and reuses modules like os.path. The tests indirectly imports modules. If os.path.exists() is mocked to always return False, we cannot import modules anymore and the test fails.

My change changes the mock to force True/False only for the path (/fakes) required by the unit test, and keep the original function for other directories, so the import machinery continues to work.

You can try to run the unit tests on Python 3.4 without my fix to see the test failing ;-)'}, {'account_id': 16708, 'date': '2015-11-10 17:21:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

* vzstorage: replace a/b with a//b to use integer division on

* fix os.path.exists mock: only override return for path /fake

commit_message:
Port vzstorage to Python 3

* vzstorage: replace a/b with a//b to use integer division on
  Python 3.
* fix os.path.exists mock: only override return for path /fake
  (shares config)
* tests-py3.txt: add cinder.tests.unit.test_vzstorage

Note: remove also spaces in parameters in two functions calls to
respect the PEP 8.

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I7cee7009d8bc87cd0294e90cb2967f4560276994

commit_message:
Swarm: Add TimeoutStartSec=300 to docker service

The default value of TimeoutStartSec=90, but it will fail on gate.
set TimeoutStartSec=300 to docker service.
It is hard to decide which one is the best choice, I tested on gate, 180 is
fine, some other guys tested on their local setup, said 4 mins, let's
hard code it as 300s first, if docker failed to start at 5 mins, it would be
failed.

see link [1] for reference.
[1] http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/systemd.service.5.html

Co-Authored-By: Kai Qiang Wu <wkqwu@cn.ibm.com>
Partially implements: blueprint swarm-functional-testing
Change-Id: I4fe4f607a2353010092ff565a7189ad3189b0ea9

commit_message:
Use olso.log directly

As the openstack/common is deprecated, Watcher should use oslo lib
directly to run in the openstack env. So there is much work to do
with oslo. This patch fixed the log part.

Change-Id: I3145a842fe3a22b3d08fec60d180329073edd50f

commit_message:
Removing translation to work with Django 1.7.x

Django 1.7.x changed such that trying to use any of the translation
functions prior to instantiating the wsgi app results in failures.

Removing all translation until it can be handled properly with
Django 1.7.x or greater.

Change-Id: I0725e64001a8ae877e6e1422d5aa8ca81e2d1aa4

commit_message:
Added gathering cron.log from nodes

Added gathering file /var/log/cron.log from the nodes.
The file uses in diagnostic snapshots.

Change-Id: I9d1ef14e2752d0a8433981b8070ab9f47e6e8a7e
Closes-Bug: #1498437

commit_message:
Adds CORS support to Cinder

This patch adds the CORS support middleware to Cinder, allowing a
deployer to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client
may break the single-origin policy and access the API directly.

For cinder, the paste.ini method of deploying the middleware was
chosen, because it needs to be able to annotate responses created
by keystonemiddleware. If the middleware was explicitly included,
keystone would reject the request before the cross-domain headers
could be annotated, resulting in an error response that is
unreadable by the user agent.

Note that tests were explicitly not included. Cinder does not
possess a functional test suite, and thus constructing any
fake application with the CORS Middleware would not correctly
test the paste.ini initialization code path.

OpenStack CrossProject Spec:
   http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/cors-support.html
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
OpenStack Cloud Admin Guide:
   http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/cross_project_cors.html
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ifac1f2c56365089a36091dc2e38d4641c135ea34

commit_message:
Use assertFalse instead of assertEqual

As the changes have been made for use of assertFalse over assertEqual
for matching false. This patch will do the same change in some
statements which were not covered by previous patches.

Change-Id: I083e7bcba27ffff13795ac5031478e07db2fed45

commit_message:
Split up test_is_volume_backed_instance() into five functions

test_is_volume_backed_instance() actually did five tests with
different object instances and test cases.  This is split up into
five separate functions with reasonable names.

Change-Id: Iba51e48413e2744ff789c8761bc9188238deb98b

commit_message:
Cleanup jeepyb and pypi-mirror special casing

We have removed them from the d-g PROJECTS list so special casing in
PBR's tests is no longer necessary.

Change-Id: I6c4a587a21a81cb2dea08d2c13ecba033b1ebee0
Depends-On: I61c2f3f8a724dc789479278e7ba493e095c52305

commit_message:
Fix impotent _poll_shelved_instances tests

Almost all of our unit tests for the _poll_shelved_intances() periodic
task were not actually running any code because they didn't set the config
properly. Some were also not setting the instance host either, which means
the test instances wouldn't be returned from the filter query. Since the
tests used stubs and mox, they weren't checking that the stubbed methods
were actually running and thus didn't notice.

This patch makes them use mock, check their work, and set the config
properly. It also does a little object and mock cleanup for the bits that
were touched.

Change-Id: If890eb61e42af3e1495da7db9033b19fa7811aa1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-14 18:02:16.000000000', 'message': "Add explicit arguments to firewall update commands

The firewall CLI relied on implicit arguments during update for
values like name, description, admin_state_up.  They worked due
to extra values parsing but were not documented in the help.

Added explicit parser arguments for values that work on the
REST resource boundary to enable help documentation and clearer
control.  This impacts firewall, firewallpolicy and firewallrule
resources.

For admin_state_up, ensured the various forms work:
Not passed, argument suppressed so update doesn't cause change
and create still defaults to up.
'--admin_state_up', with no extra parameter - defaults to True
'--admin_state_up=True', '--admin_state_up True', '--admin_state_up 1'
forms continue to work.

For shared flag, also enabled various forms to allow update means
to change a rule/policy from 'shared true' to 'shared false' via
'--shared=False'.

Added common argument parsing for firewall rules between create
and update due to number of arguments.

Change-Id: Ifbd2a42f0cf574cbd7405df51181d95538a7edcb
Closes-Bug: #1503642

Added explicit parser arguments for values that work on the
REST resource boundary to enable help documentation and clearer
control.  This impacts firewall, firewallpolicy and firewallrule
resources.

For admin_state_up, ensured the various forms work:
Not passed, argument suppressed so update doesn't cause change

commit_message:
FWaaS: Add explicit arguments to update commands

The firewall CLI relied on implicit arguments during update for
values like name, description, admin_state_up.  They worked due
to extra values parsing but were not documented in the help.

Added explicit parser arguments for values that work on the
REST resource boundary to enable help documentation and clearer
control.  This impacts firewall, firewallpolicy and firewallrule
resources.

For admin_state_up, ensured the various forms work:
Not passed, argument suppressed so update doesn't cause change
and create still defaults to up.
'--admin_state_up', with no extra parameter - defaults to True
'--admin_state_up=True', '--admin_state_up True', '--admin_state_up 1'
forms continue to work.

For shared flag, also enabled various forms to allow update means
to change a rule/policy from 'shared true' to 'shared false' via
'--shared=False'.

Added common argument parsing for firewall rules between create
and update due to number of arguments.

Change-Id: Ifbd2a42f0cf574cbd7405df51181d95538a7edcb
Closes-Bug: #1503642

commit_message:
VMware: use oslo_config new type PortOpt

Now oslo_config provides new type PortOpt for
validating Port, min and max port are no need here.

Change-Id: I2ad2811285aec4897c79b151ac2245d483b36876

commit_message:
Validate nova server's metadata

This prevents "foo" getting passed into the metadata.
This can happen when using get_attr() to return a dynamic value.

Change-Id: I17eab659e65a51963e510add4d71fbc90a3a3a53
Closes-bug: #1338811
(cherry picked from commit 22df43e2f1e4dd6050e61f0808e6970b0cb05dac)

commit_message:
set min_compute_nodes when running in multinode mode

To ensure that our multinode configurations actually have multiple
working workers, we're building some tests in Tempest that attempt to
land on every node by using scheduler hints (force_hosts). This
requires that we set the minimum number of nodes that are expected to
be found in a configuration (it defaults to 1).

Change-Id: I59ca8b76dc3fe0c62236de11dbf44d52fa37226a
Depends-On: I7d7230d100901179a1d1a0281aa8be990d00c02a

commit_message:
Make sure template resource's metadata is refreshed

This copies the code snippet from instance.py, which refreshes
the metadata when we get a signal on a referenced resource.

Note: a functional test is coming in a later commit.

Closes-bug: 1418942
Change-Id: I5980c9cf4dc355b9bfa93273bc26a768ab9abdb8
(cherry picked from commit e5ffaff0b3326bcf2840f781501b9f7bb6513ccd)

commit_message:
Update template paths for environment-mapped TemplateResources

When updating a template resource, we weren't taking into account the
possibility that the new environment could be mapping the resource to a
different template path. This change ensures we recalculate the template
name from the new environment before reloading the template during an
update.

Change-Id: I5f84f6fd60925d3dba0b8e8dec867657c8c5c9ef
Closes-Bug: #1452534
(cherry picked from commit 686f317ccae280bd8b536379e89ba743746ae159)

commit_message:
Guestagent configuration tests mock chown/chmod

Avoid executing chmod and chown OS calls in configuration manager tests
as they may cause failures on various platforms.
Do not assert the mocked calls as testing them is not intent here.

Change-Id: Ib858c74a4ec09d13b34858290ae7f38864a998b0
Closes-Bug: 1515328

commit_message:
Tolerate missing template resource type

If a template resource type is added during a stack-update, the update
will fail because the old environment is used on some code paths until
the update completes.

This change falls back to TemplateResource if a ResourceTypeNotFound is
raised. Previously this only happened when TemplateNotFound is raised.

Change-Id: Id040c8f7ab1231056c67cf363bf26168a5684340
Closes-Bug: #1508096

commit_message:
Fix race in _poll_shelved_instances task

The _poll_shelved_instances() task can race with other API operations
because it does not filter instances with a task_state!=None, and because
it does not use expected_task_state=(None,) when it attempts to lock the
instance for offloading. This patch adds those checks as well as tests to
make sure they're honored going forward.

Change-Id: I7b1e235a4d09085cebf3d6d71d71757f15f69e29

commit_message:
Images CLI improvement

* fixing representation after image is registered
* adding ability to register images by name
* adding additional ut

Partially implements: blueprint cli-as-openstackclient-plugin

commit_message:
validate non-ascii values for swift properties

skip properties that are non-ascii values, but proceed
with properties that work. log these failed values back
to the user.

commit_message:
Add fip pool param to Blue Box nodepool config

This is required in order for nodepool to find the right floating
ips.

Change-Id: I0324d51ad09b93b36e760a95946e27236edf3c08

commit_message:
Fix failure of unit test TestCinderAllCmd

After introducing the commit 93d26e40098c966e7d791a9fb6152244a9f9409d
unit test TestCinderAllCmd fails if a test environment has
/etc/cinder/cinder.conf with proper backend configuration.
We should mock out some variables not to depend on test environment.

Change-Id: I3218f6be1c38ed228aa96346d6976a04ecb8d421
Closes-Bug: #1513263
(cherry picked from commit c10beb9fc0105d570ce87e4adb242b4393054862)

removing zookeeper devstack lib

devstack added zookeeper to the main devstack repo, so a custom
zookeeper lib is no longer necessary

commit_message:
[WIP] Support for Glance v2

This is extremely WIPy and not ready for consumption. Only a basic
read-only wrapper is implemented for now. V1 should still work as
usual, v2 should work as read-only. Metadata/properties stuff with v2
entirely tbd.

Remaining TODOs:
- Fix failing tests / panel registration issue
- Properly use the APIVersionManager
- Stop hardcoding versions in glance.py
- Create / Update [ without messing the properties ]
- Unit tests for v1 and v2, test_data for both versions
- *A LOT* of work with properties, custom properties
- Also: handle case when custom properties are disabled

Implements blueprint: horizon-glance-v2
Co-Authored-By: Travis Tripp <travis.tripp@hp.com>

Change-Id: If4103df2b1a3860baf3dc15d424f9a6b352166c0

commit_message:
Enable space-in-parens

This rule will enforce consistency of spacing directly inside of
parentheses, by disallowing or requiring one or more spaces to
the right of ( and to the left of ). In either case, () will still
be allowed.

Change-Id: I83edef0598f82c2b34fd3a4d7262b6ea9204d2b3

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-21 00:04:45.000000000', 'message': 'This patch set adds support for add/delete router interfaces.
Adding router port involves:
    - Create row in logical_router_port table
    - Update the ports in logical_router table with the
    logical_router_port added above
    - Update the options column in logical_port table with
    {router-port: "UUID of logical_router_port"}
    - set the type column in the logical_port table to "router"

Deleting router ports:
    - Look for port_id if port_id not present in incoming request
    - Delete the router port from the logical_router table
    The logical_router_port entry will be garbage collected

Change-Id: I6fd9ac4ab04be14796422087d3ff716cd4d81e55

commit_message:
Add/delete router interfaces

This patch set adds support for add/delete router interfaces.
Adding router port involves:
    - Create row in logical_router_port table
    - Update the ports in logical_router table with the
    logical_router_port added above
    - Update the options column in logical_port table with
    {router-port: "UUID of logical_router_port"}
    - set the type column in the logical_port table to "router"

Deleting router ports:
    - Look for port_id if port_id not present in incoming request
    - Delete the router port from the logical_router table
    The logical_router_port entry will be garbage collected

Added a config variable OVN_L3_MODE which when set to false,
will default to using q-l3 instead of OVN L3. This is a temporary fix
until we resolve OVN l3 issues.

Closes-Bug: #1514649
Change-Id: I6fd9ac4ab04be14796422087d3ff716cd4d81e55
Co-Authored-By: Gal Sagie <gal.sagie@huawei.com>
Co-Authored-By: Amitabha Biswas <abiswas@us.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Add retries to TestRail client

In order to workaround API limitations (such as
requests rate), adding mechanism of requests
retries based on predefined error codes.

Try to resend request 3 times if '429' code is
received from API.

Closes-bug: #1514797
Change-Id: I723ef7886c86b7e418627962a1ff8aa7a4281c0a

y'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-11-06 14:01:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So basically if you get the cloud image from here https://getfedora.org/en/cloud/download/ , you will have 'python3' installed and python3 is a working command.

At first the:
# python --version
-bash: python: command not found


You have two options here:
1. create python named symbolic-link to python3
2. install the python named package which is python2

On the image the python main script files (for example pyvenv ), starts with #!/usr/bin/python3.4

The python3 command works as usual."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-11-06 14:23:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

sudo dnf install -y python2 # also installs python2'}, {'account_id': 7715, 'date': '2015-11-09 23:43:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

I got it.

What if "python" command means python3 in a case that devstack user uses a tool like pyenv and other use case? It's better to confirm whether the version is 2 or 3.'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-11-11 04:40:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I think this is the simplest thing

I guess a switch has to be made at some point

I think that if "python" does not refer to python2 then every script ever written that has #!/usr/bin/env python and has assumed that is python2 will break, so I think it's a fair assumption'}, {'account_id': 16788, 'date': '2015-11-11 05:49:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6962, 'date': '2015-11-12 11:44:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Ensure python is installed

devstack can call python before parsing the
package requirements, so the python installation
needs to be done eralier.

Closes-Bug: #1488625

commit_message:
Small cleanup for unit/proxy/controllers/test_obj

Follow up for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/236007

This fixes following minor items:

- Fix a 'raise Exception class' syntax to 'raise Exception instance'
- Use original eventlet.Timeout instead of swift.exceptions.Timeout
  imported from eventlet.Timeout
- Change Timeout to initiate w/o args (1st arguments should be timeout
  second and we don't have to set None if we don't want to set the sec)
- Add a message argument to some Exception instances

Change-Id: Iab608cd8a1f4d3f5b4963c26b94ab0501837ffe1

commit_message:
Make "Connect(ing|ed) to AMQP server" log messages DEBUG level

According to our guidelines, INFO level is for unit-of-work messages
valueable for an operator. This rules out "connecting" message.
As to "connected", while it might fall under guidelines, it seems
to flood logs without too much value, see for example:
http://logs.openstack.org/98/219298/9/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-ironic-pxe_ipa/53784fb/logs/screen-ir-api.txt.gz?level=INFO

Change-Id: I65e0f19590c42d25e5551d45af37416a01a7d638

commit_message:
Adding .pre-version file for packaging process

Packaging requires the existence of this file to determine the
version of pbr the package needs.

Change-Id: Iaa14f55732ffb608ce33f2377513ff0c33706c6d

commit_message:
Decompose mechanism driver out of neutron completely

Move the driver, shim test, and entrypoint here. This allows us to completely
remove opendaylight code from the neutron tree.

Partial-Bug: #1514823

commit_message:
Remove TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in the api tox env

Setting TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in tox.ini is breaking the gate,
probably because of a tox bug [1].
Removing the line to unblock the gate. This implies that
for local execution of the tests TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR
should be set manually.

commit_message:
Make amphora ssh access configurable

It some instances it is required to not allow access to the Amphora.
In order to solve both cases make the option configurable.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1515078

Change-Id: I8a04ca86e4111c44a0bf44c8993b87a7acc334a2

commit_message:
Pin werkzeug to sub 0.11 for now

Werkzeug has trouble with reload (needed for cert rotation) and
SSL in the latest release 0.11.x - so pinning it to the last
"working" for now.

We expect this to be fixed in the next maintenance release of
werkzeug and hecne won't make that fix permanent.

Change-Id: Iacc1906ce3091322c8a1e9dbdf6392c77f3807b5
Closes-Bug: 1514644

[{'created': '2015-11-11 22:59:23.000000000', 'message': 'Fix grab console log partial gets

The grab console log script started by cleaning out any existing console
log files with echo. Unfortunately echo appends a newline by default
which meant we ended up with a 1 byte file instead of a 0 byte file.
This resulted in grabbing the console log from byte offset 1 instead of
0 and jenkins is weird and prepended base64 content at the beginning of
the log file in this case.

Fix this by using echo -n to clear the file which results in a 0 byte
file.

Change-Id: I8bd7cbd0c19cd44067839b34e317248daad9f578
'}]
commit_message:
Fix grab console log partial gets

The grab console log script started by cleaning out any existing console
log files with echo. Unfortunately echo appends a newline by default
which meant we ended up with a 1 byte file instead of a 0 byte file.
This resulted in grabbing the console log from byte offset 1 instead of
0 and jenkins is weird and prepended base64 content at the beginning of
the log file in this case.

Fix this by using echo -n to clear the file which results in a 0 byte
file.

Change-Id: I8bd7cbd0c19cd44067839b34e317248daad9f578

commit_message:
Adds config to disable the password in stack

Currently a password is needed when doing a stack creation using
Horizon. This patch adds a configurable setting in local_settings.py
file, so that it can be disabled from the stack creation form.

Change-Id: I82783b73940e39d961ac70a5ce86abdaca02eba7
Closes-bug: #1290344
Co-Authored-By: Richard Jones <r1chardj0n3s@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Jesse Keating <jlk@bluebox.net>

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "Remove TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in the api tox env""

This reverts commit 286f5d41dc255c711a3fcb0d978b63752deb2bbd.

The revert was merged too quickly, without waiting for tox project to fix us.
The gate passed for the revert only because infra folks removed images
that had new tox in them. We will be broken by the next images though.

Change-Id: Idad2c656e4271d1222e6f8939eb90c6353e1fe67

[{'created': '2015-11-09 07:24:21.000000000', 'message': 'avoid unnecessary inner join in get_resources() for SQL backend

To get distinct resource ids, we do a query on resource table which
inner join sample table, and apply filters on it.

Note that when sql_expire_samples_only is enabled, there will be
some resources without any sample, in such case we must use inner
join to avoid wrong result, no matter if there is a timestamp filter
or not.

But that option is disabled by default, so when there is no timestamp
filters, the inner join is unnecessary, we should avoid it to save

Change-Id: If85dbea15d42d42c6b0be7402c06f258e278b2eb

commit_message:
avoid unnecessary inner join in get_resources() for SQL backend

To get distinct resource ids, we do a query on resource table which
inner join sample table, and apply filters on it.

Note that when sql_expire_samples_only is enabled, there will be
some resources without any sample, in such case we must use inner
join to avoid wrong result, no matter if there is a timestamp filter
or not.

But that option is disabled by default, so when there is no timestamp
filters, the inner join is unnecessary, we should avoid it to save
some RAM/CPU cost.

Change-Id: If85dbea15d42d42c6b0be7402c06f258e278b2eb
Closes-Bug: #1509677
(cherry picked from commit a4f442940551a8a38e26e132c7efa766226daa15)

Change-Id: I261a2dd362ed51c16a6fa191dadcce1b45fce2e4

commit_message:
avoid generate temporary table when query samples

Currently, when we call query-samples API, for SQL backend, we do
an inner join to get a temporary table, then apply filters, orderby
and limit options on it. Such implementation will drain disk space
or cause timeout exception when data set is growing, even with specified
limit and filters.

This patch applies filters and limit on the inner join itself, and
uses a fake mapper object instead of temporary table to suit current
query transformer.

Change-Id: I261a2dd362ed51c16a6fa191dadcce1b45fce2e4
Closes-Bug: #1506738
(cherry picked from commit b9bf5f1f571f21aee4347c80a5a7ac8a1c456e45)

commit_message:
Remove unused compat variable SCREEN_DEV

Currently we set USE_SCREEN to SCREEN_DEV if it's set.  There is a
comment to remove it once it's eracticated from CI.

AFAICT this pre-condition has been met.

Change-Id: I1423c8b9c18d1b3e34dbfe1c03be735c646a12b4

commit_message:
Demo patch for ironic panel index page

Steps:
- Login as admin, you should see `Ironic` in Admin dashboard
  > Systems panel group
- Click on it, you should see a page with `Nodes` as page title
  and a table listing the nodes in the current region. You should be
  able to:

  - setect nodes;
  - power on/off slected nodes;
  - put selected nodes to maintenance mode, or remove them from
    maintenance mode.

Change-Id: I0a15c2985578c03ca9ac43e4a42596f1c301f161

commit_message:
Creating Ironic APIs

This patch implements Ironic APIs at all layers

- Client-side angular Ironic API service.
- Server-side rest Ironic API for Ajax.
- Server-side Ironic API using Python ironic client.

APIs include:

- Retrieve a list of nodes.
- Retrieve details for a node.
- List all the ports with a given node.
- Set power state on/off for a given node.
- Set maintenance mode state on/off for a given node.

Change-Id: I759114186359d41c65bb9713ac6a86c6860ed923
Partially-Implements: blueprint ng-admin-ironic-panel

commit_message:
Demo patch for enabling admin ironic panel

Steps:
- Login as admin, you should see `Ironic` in Admin dashboard
  > Systems panel group
- Click on it, you should see a page with `Nodes` as page title.
- Change URL to http://localhost:9000/admin/ironic/123, you should
  see a page a page with `Node Details` as page title.

Change-Id: I75c60da7fe0874c8f129e60908a5f9d097bb42fa

[{'created': '2015-10-15 21:49:47.000000000', 'message': 'Creating admin ironic panel

This patch adds a new ironic panel to admin dashboard to:

Current horizon allows an admin to see that nodes are managed by
Ironic, and determine which instance is running on each. This is
probably enough when there are no errors, but troubleshooting and
maintenance will be much easier if the UI overview includes:

* current power state - is a node on...or off?
* current provisioning state - where in the process is this node?
* if node in maintenance - is it available for provisioning right now?

The admin experience is better still if each node can be expanded
to reveal details about each node such as what drivers are associated
with a node, why it is in maintenance, when was the last error, etc.

The implementation of this panel is angular-based.

To enable the panel, set DISABLED = False in
openstack_dashboard/enabled/_2121_admin_ironic.py

commit_message:
Creating admin ironic panel

This patch adds an empty ironic panel to admin dashboard, which
is a part of implementation for a fully working ironic panel.
When the implementation completed, it will provide these features 
to Horizon:

As an admin, I can:

* get a list of all the nodes in a given region.
* check and modify power state for a node.
* check and modify maintenance state for a node.
* check all other detailed information of a given node.

The implementation is angular-based.

Testing: a demo patch is provided for testing.

Change-Id: I515f3b348bee09b1f6b4602dfb5ce48a465d41bd
Partially-Implements: blueprint ng-admin-ironic-panel

[{'created': '2015-11-12 20:13:23.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Add magnum support to functional tests on shade"

The magnum devstack plugin does not conform to our expectations of
how a project should interact with our CI system.  It downloads
an opaque image from a fedorapeople hosted site.

Instead, it should build an image using our CI system, host it
on tarballs.o.o, and, assuming it is not too large, be cached by
our image builds.

Until it does that, we should not use it in other projects.

This reverts commit 9cf8601417c74714fd7e56ee68ff4723f5933731.

Change-Id: I9c887ceb2585fb092dce3e400758b6dc9f32acde
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Add magnum support to functional tests on shade"

The magnum devstack plugin does not conform to our expectations of
how a project should interact with our CI system.  It downloads
an opaque image from a fedorapeople hosted site.

Instead, it should build an image using our CI system, host it
on tarballs.o.o, and, assuming it is not too large, be cached by
our image builds.

Until it does that, we should not use it in other projects.

This reverts commit 9cf8601417c74714fd7e56ee68ff4723f5933731.

Change-Id: I9c887ceb2585fb092dce3e400758b6dc9f32acde

commit_message:
Enable metadata when create server groups

instance_group object already support instance group metadata but
heat resource do not support this.
This patch was enabling metadata support when creating instance
group as heat resource.

Change-Id: I20a8b30fc177353ef64a8a06e9d1c6219b21b045
Partial-Bug: #1348447

Update Devstack deployment and docs

Move the devstack files inside Barbican tree. Also updates
the devstack documentation for installing barbican via
vagrant or manually.

commit_message:
skip tempest/unit tests on api-guide only changes

The api-guide is documentation, and should get the same skip-if rules
as the rest of the doc trees in nova. This will encourage
contributions that just help fix the api-guide.

Change-Id: Id3714af25bdbbe4be05dbf9a9e8db1f8a489a588

commit_message:
Add common config options to san

This patch copies three config options from storwize_svc driver
to the base san driver in order to minimize duplicating
of config options within the storwize_svc driver.
This accommodates removing of the aforementioned config options
in the future as a part of our refactoring process.

This patch is part of a series of patches with the aim of
bringing the storwize_svc driver in line with other san based
Cinder drivers.

Co-Authored By: Jacob Gregor <jgregor@us.ibm.com>

Partially implements: blueprint refactor-storwize-driver-for-mitaka

Change-Id: If2361a706e10725e343efc0993523f6c9059fe34

commit_message:
Update version to 3.4

The jobs in OpenStack run against Python 3.4.  This change set updates
the setup.cfg to also reflect this version.

Also provides a proper homepage for the project.

Change-Id: I78a5c2dfd7219cea9b70e739d4bf43e55ab29277

API to expand the volume capacity. A volume copy is being
used to achieve the expansion for performance reasons,

commit_message:
NetApp: Fix issue with E-Series volume expand

The volume extend operation is using the wrong backend
API to expand the volume capacity. A volume copy is being
used to achieve the expansion for performance reasons,
but this results in snapshots defined on the original
volume being lost.

This patch updates the volume extend API to use the correct
method for expanding the volume capacity. For a thin-provisioned
volume or a volume defined on a DDP, this operation is very fast.
However, for a standard volume-group, this method will block
until the expansion has completed, because the expansion capacity
will not be available until completion.

Closes-Bug: 1506212
Change-Id: I1cb91b96ede732a76204287043b63a2a67f805f4

[{'account_id': 18401, 'date': '2015-11-04 20:48:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-04 20:53:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-python-tackerclient-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/62/241762/2/check/gate-python-tackerclient-pep8/246a3dc/ : SUCCESS in 1m 42s'}, {'account_id': 12455, 'date': '2015-11-05 02:07:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

It is a nice feature for tacker, but I have few suggestions.

1)I feel it is better to have template download command instead of template show. If the user specify file path, we can store the contents to that file, otherwise print to console.

For ex:
tacker vnfd-download sample-vnfd
template_name: sample-vnfd
description: demo-example
.....
.....

tacker vnfd-download -f sample-vnfd.yaml sample-vnfd
(Creates 'sample-vnfd.yaml' and store the contents of sample-vnfd)

2)If the output of the server for the show command changes, we need to change the code in run(), because it is hardcoded now. So why don't we have a seperate API for this, so that it gives only template and is independent of show command."}, {'account_id': 18401, 'date': '2015-11-05 08:41:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks for your comments.

1) I would not change parameter name, since it is kind of standard to use "show" postfix for this kind of usage. Users can use redirection to store output to file, but I can add a option if it is necessary (tacker vnfd-template-show sample-vnfd > /tmp/out.yaml).

2) For now the path to template ("vnfd" -> "attributes" -> "vnfd") is described in MANO API [1]. But I agree with you that there could be a separate API for getting templates.

Anyway it would be best to see some comments/suggestions from other core developers.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/tacker/blob/master/doc/source/devref/mano_api.rst'}, {'account_id': 12455, 'date': '2015-11-05 10:09:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

show is to get details of a particular resource not for an attribute of a particular resource. But I also agree with you. And I was referring to glance image-download'}, {'account_id': 12455, 'date': '2015-11-05 10:10:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Yeah let's see some other 'core developers' suggestions"}, {'account_id': 16511, 'date': '2015-11-05 14:33:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think the template-show command is fine.  It is trivial for the user to redirect the output of a template-show command into a file, so it is not necessary to implement an option to save to a file.  Glance is dealing with binary files which don't need to be displayed to a terminal, so I think that's a different scenario.

I would not change the API for this use case - the server should provide the data and the client should manipulate the display of the data as needed.

Overall I think it looks fine but I want to play with it a bit in my testbed, and also get sridhar_ram's input.

Also need to check what might be possible for automated testing of this feature.

Good work"}, {'account_id': 16511, 'date': '2015-11-09 20:15:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Tested fine for me.  I verified that the output of the command redirected to a file matches the original input file, which is as expected.  Adding sridhar_ram for his input.'}, {'account_id': 18401, 'date': '2015-11-10 09:47:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Ok great, and thank you guys for your time. Now we wait for Sridhar.'}, {'account_id': 13380, 'date': '2015-11-10 10:53:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(6 comments)

Hi Luka,

First of, this is a very very useful feature. In fact I'd vote to incorporate this into our Horizon UI to display VNFD template.

I've few code level comments inline. But the main sticking point is introducing a new command for this - which is kind of significant IMO. We already have "vnfd-show" command. Can we make this an optional flag for that same command like,

tacker vnfd-show --template <name / uuid>

Last comment, you cannot give a +1 to your own patchset ;)'}, {'account_id': 18401, 'date': '2015-11-10 17:18:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-10 17:22:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-python-tackerclient-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/62/241762/3/check/gate-python-tackerclient-pep8/a244b3e/ : SUCCESS in 1m 01s'}, {'account_id': 18401, 'date': '2015-11-10 17:22:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Ok, I fixed stuff mentioned in inline comments...

> We already have "vnfd-show" command. Can we make this an optional flag for that same command like,
> tacker vnfd-show --template <name / uuid>

Hm, I am not able to add --template parameter to "vnfd-show" command and get a nice output of template file (plain file with preserved newlines).

At least not without major code changes. The reason for this is that tackerV10.ShowCommand uses tables to display parameters. I think we would need to override "run()" method somehow, only when --template parameter is used? I am not sure if this is OK? Any help/suggestions on this topic are appreciated...

BTW, heat also uses separate option for showing template (heat template-show <stack-id>). For Tacker I used "vnfd" prefix, because some other templates may be supported in the future (like NSD template for example).

> In fact I'd vote to incorporate this into our Horizon UI to display VNFD template.

This would be great. It could be implemented similar like in heat UI (Orchestration -> Stacks -> Stack-details -> Template).

> Last comment, you cannot give a +1 to your own patchset ;)

Haha, sorry about that, it was a mistake :)'}, {'account_id': 16511, 'date': '2015-11-11 02:33:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

I agree with the heat template-show comparison.  The tacker vnfd-show output is hard to read with the attributes/template included, so it might be worthwhile to consider removing that column from the vnfd-show output once this is available.'}, {'account_id': 18401, 'date': '2015-11-11 08:45:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thanks Bob.

I gave it another try, and I came up with another patch [1] to support "tacker vnfd-show <vnfd-name/id> --template".

But I think that current patch set (PS3) looks better from usage and code point of view. Please let me know what do you think and I can push the new PS, if it is necessary or you can merge current PS.

[1] Patch: https://gist.github.com/KLuka/d8a88a31e38ca0bcf7e0'}, {'account_id': 2874, 'date': '2015-11-12 08:07:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Adding an OSSN for bug 1456228 - Trusted VM powered on untrusted host

OpenStack Trusted Computing Pools does not call remote Attestation API to
check whether the host is trust or not when a trusted VM is powered
on. This makes it possible to power on a trusted VM on an untrusted host.

Closes-Bug #1456228

Change-Id: Id81df58cdaa9dd58d885f0b6c4b98e46a2e305ba

[{'account_id': 15333, 'date': '2015-11-12 13:43:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 14676, 'date': '2015-11-12 13:45:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

What is the reason behind this? Is this documentation going to be official docs?'}, {'account_id': 15333, 'date': '2015-11-12 13:49:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yes, you can visit the official PostgreSQL website: http://www.postgresql.org/. "PostgreSQL" is the correct spelling, and "postgreSQL" is not.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-12 14:16:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-glance-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/62/244662/1/check/gate-glance-specs-docs/3c4a1a9//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 3m 15s
- gate-glance-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/62/244662/1/check/gate-glance-specs-python27/cd0c4d4/ : SUCCESS in 2m 44s'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2015-11-12 16:43:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think Kairat's question wasn't "what's the official spelling of PostgreSQL?" but rather, "why do we want to modify an approved spec for a minor spelling change?"'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2015-11-12 16:51:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Our attitude has been that we don't want to hold up specs for minor imperfections that could be patched later.  So now we have a test of that attitude, since it feels very strange to make changes to an approved spec.

To answer Kairat's question, the specs are "sort of" documentation, and they are publicly exposed at specs.openstack.org ... so it's a good thing that they be correct with respect to what was actually implemented, and also correct in other aspects (spelling, grammar).

e9268e9 Functional tests for os-extended-server-attributes
5f5ec35 Add v2 support for optional project_id in version discovery urls
c6a3c76 Check flavor option before image checks
4f16fe6 make project_id optional in urls for version discovery
09bb834 Refactor parsing metadata to a common function

'}]
commit_message:
mitaka: release python-novaclient 2.35.0

We want to do this minor release to get some things flushed out before
we start tackling backwards incompatible changes that will trigger a
major version bump to 3.0, like removing the novaclient.v1_1 module.

Changes since 2.34.0:

e9268e9 Functional tests for os-extended-server-attributes
5f5ec35 Add v2 support for optional project_id in version discovery urls
c6a3c76 Check flavor option before image checks
4f16fe6 make project_id optional in urls for version discovery
09bb834 Refactor parsing metadata to a common function

The upper-constraints change is:

I07d33438cd5f13c5c16498b4b275eead7bac244b

Change-Id: I4552b113efd8087ac942405c3c75e12da0f26d71

commit_message:
Changing the way baseline formatters are indicated

This commit adds a decorator for formatters to use to indicate
that they are able to display baseline results.  A formatter
should add @accepts_baseline before the report function to show
that it is capable of displaying candidate results.

Change-Id: I5532d4b322b7df9dbca8a2275bf6e273d2801a3a

commit_message:
Ironic: Explicitly allow DHCP ports

This adds an iptables rule to allow ports 67 and 68. We see
occassionally dropped DHCP packets, which may be causing PXE failures in
ironic jobs.

I'm not 100% confident this fixes the issue, however I don't think it
can break anything and it rules out one theory.

Change-Id: I4630afb6f010a4c2cb146a79264c480c64c6e4b7
Related-Bug: #1393099

Oh, no more inline comments after merge... So I'll post here just for the record.

I agree this is too verbose. Let me examine possibilities of Jinja2 more closely and see what shortest clear notation I can come up with.

If I don't find anything better, {{ 'oslo.i18n' | py2pkg }} looks like reasonable fallback to me.

I'm against custom .spec macros because they're extra build time requirements. Let's render a vanilla .spec for each supported target.

Finally, we could apply context sensitive automagic as Alan suggests, but I think maintaining such rules centrally would be quite a pain due to all the special cases here and there which can be easily hacked with explicit Jinja tags."}]

commit_message:
Use kilo RDO repository

Use kilo RDO repository on kilo branch.

Note we slightly change the check here to just accept any
pre-installed RDO; devstack-gate might have installed the latest for
us, because it needs openvswitch to setup multi-node testing, which is
just about the only thing we use from RDO.

Change-Id: I42b8bc1aea8ff61770987eecd5fc3b8309c1e210

commit_message:
Do not remove python-pip package on Fedora-23

python on fedora 23 compiled with rewheel support,
in this case the python-pip is a required package, and cannot be
removed.

[1] http://pkgs.fedoraproject.org/cgit/python.git/tree/python.spec?id=3b6fac0339bab69ca5fbf2881568f0565ab0e252#n174

Change-Id: I499b7bec97c4360b32d156079f2b7f3923e3888a

Fix the install package in RDO install guide.
This has been changed from python-keystone-auth-token
to python-keystoneclient.

Change-Id: If0dd22e42a5acf297dfbcdd1e2fb43770e3021d0
Closes-Bug: #1515606

commit_message:
Modify 'is_default' behavior relative to 'is_protected' for templates

With the addition of the general *is_protected* field on all objects,
the *is_default* field on cluster and node group templates is semi-redundant.
Its semantics should be changed; specifically, gating of update and
delete operations should be handled exclusively by *is_protected*. The
*is_default* field should still be used to identify default templates for bulk
update and delete operations by the sahara-templates tool.

Partial-implements: blueprint replace-is-default
Change-Id: I9808df9546636d755fc9c999ebee45e1ec9f2b1a

commit_message:
Python3: fix glance.tests.unit.v2.test_images_resource

Two issues here:
- jsonutils.dump_as_bytes should be used since request.body needs to be
  set to bytes;
- in Python 3, calling "del o[:]" makes us end up in __delslice__ with
  "i" and "j" being None, hence the little trick in glance/location.py.

Change-Id: Iff191305ab55f67801183127077fc8ae9738e763

commit_message:
create actions when creating jobs

When creating a job, the api manages the actions contained
therein.
This is to enforce any action in any job to have an action_id
so that the editing from the web-ui is supported.

The behavior is the following:

  - an action with no action_id is created with new action_id
  - an action with a new action_id is created with that action_id
  - an action with an existing action_id is compared to the action
    already existing in the action db.
    If the action is different, it is inserted with a new action_id

Change-Id: I436a35efce87968def92f41c4e66bda0beabc677

commit_message:
Delete the gate-grenade-dsvm-ironic-sideways job

This job only runs in stable/juno and was meant to test the
transition from nova baremetal to ironic, which people should have
done by now.

Also, the job appears to be busted in stable/juno and it's blocking
things from getting into the final 2014.2.4 release before we EOL
the branch, so let's delete it now.

Change-Id: I7128f4c6bbcf2250d4e57d214d04086ea4db542e

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "Remove TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in the api tox env""

This reverts commit 286f5d41dc255c711a3fcb0d978b63752deb2bbd.

The revert was merged too quickly, without waiting for tox project to fix us.
The gate passed for the revert only because infra folks removed images
that had new tox in them. We will be broken by the next images though.

Change-Id: Iabd61f18ba65cbfe5b276e3f375175b61d7b3634

commit_message:
Use keystoneauth to create a Session

All client interactions should actually flow through a keystoneauth
Session. Add the parameter for a user to pass one in, but support
the old style of direct parameters too. A followup patch will add
os-client-config support to the shell, so add that to requirements.txt
instead of keystoneauth directly to look forward.

Also, trim unneeded things from requirements.txt because we're adding
os-client-config which pulls in various things.

Closes-Bug: #1514733
Change-Id: I88b1d0e4e119429599dec75c5db24237a92edcec

commit_message:
Move USER operation after footer

The USER operation affects all docker commands after it. This causes a
problem with our {{ include_footer }} implementation since commands in
that footer may require elevated permissions to perform.

In the current implementation I can no longer remove my proxy settings
once the USER has been changed.

Change-Id: I9b2bab5a15f595f6d52a46c64ddf59ba5608b938
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
Add override variables for plugin

Allow a plugin to override the admin and public addresses using
swift_hash:

- swift_hash['management_vip']
- swift_hash['public_vip']

Partially implements: blueprint detach-components-from-controllers
Change-Id: I90f727451081052c14e0bea896f6faab01f15486

commit_message:
Fixed conflics with slashes in requests

Requests containing slashes can confuse the routing of queries in the api.
Therefore slashes need to be encoded.

This add the decoding part to the receiving part.

Change-Id: Iabc4699dd082ae52db78455e79b7c9b3b6215393

commit_message:
Invalid output running the command 'glance image-show <image_id>'

Running the command returns the string 'id' and fails on exception.
In function _image_meta_from_headers the meta variable was not properly
set because key was not lowercased. Converting key to lowercase solves
the problem.

NOTE: this is a compatibility fix for urllib3 >= 1.11

Closes-Bug: #1487645
Co-Authored-by: Flavio Percoco <flavio@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I1b0b327163577585becb5e762536058d21dc1c98
(cherry picked from commit 2c7da7cb6077b89a7e195f76ed092ea7dfe65e02)

[{'created': '2015-10-21 20:04:57.000000000', 'message': "Include registry on update when other envs are specified

On an openstack overcloud deploy which results in a stack-update,
implicitly include overcloud-resource-registry-puppet.yaml if the user
specifies any other custom environments. Do not include
overcloud-resource-registry-puppet.yaml if the user specifies no extra
environments.

This solution would be an improvement over the current situation, but it
isn't perfect.

It does the right thing when:
- the user does an openstack overcloud with no environments specified
- the user does an openstack overcloud with all custom environments
  specified

It will sometimes do the wrong thing when:
- the user specifies a partial list of custom environments (like -e
  do_my_custom_oneoff_thing.yaml)

Change-Id: I60fbf2182429f6bb83e000fc4d45269d7f83171b
Related-Bug: #1498607

commit_message:
Include registry on update when other envs are specified

On an openstack overcloud deploy which results in a stack-update,
implicitly include overcloud-resource-registry-puppet.yaml if the user
specifies any other custom environments. Do not include
overcloud-resource-registry-puppet.yaml if the user specifies no extra
environments.

This solution would be an improvement over the current situation, but it
isn't perfect.

It does the right thing when:
- the user does an openstack overcloud with no environments specified
- the user does an openstack overcloud with all custom environments
  specified

It will sometimes do the wrong thing when:
- the user specifies a partial list of custom environments (like -e
  do_my_custom_oneoff_thing.yaml)

Change-Id: I60fbf2182429f6bb83e000fc4d45269d7f83171b
Related-Bug: #1498607
Closes-Bug: #1504363

Change-Id: I03ff193cac487e9564d53438699f66eaf3b3d412

I'm conflicted on this one.  Normally I advocate using positional arguments for items that are required, though obviously this did not use that convention before.  Also, there are so many options to the boot command that adding another required argument may become unwieldy…

Would love to hear thoughts from other reviewers on this one; do we change this (in a backwards-compatible way) to listing a positional argument for flavor, or do we stick with making a required option?"}, {'account_id': 16907, 'date': '2015-10-07 16:30:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Of the 4600+ lines in shell.py, there is currently only one `required=True`.

https://github.com/openstack/python-novaclient/blob/03f1f67ccde6f495e264da08f0bb7d707cf3ff66/novaclient/v2/shell.py#L4194

Note how it behaves (calling 'tenant' both 'required' and 'optional' which is confusing):

$ nova help quota-delete
usage: nova quota-delete --tenant <tenant-id> [--user <user-id>]

Delete quota for a tenant/user so their quota will Revert back to default.

Optional arguments:
  --tenant <tenant-id>  ID of tenant to delete quota for.
  --user <user-id>      ID of user to delete quota for.

$ nova quota-delete
usage: nova quota-delete --tenant <tenant-id> [--user <user-id>]
error: argument --tenant is required

Also note the tip from the Python docs:

https://docs.python.org/3/library/argparse.html#required

"Required options are generally considered bad form because users expect options to be optional, and thus they should be avoided when possible."

I don't think we should introduce a second `required=True` in this case.'}, {'account_id': 16907, 'date': '2015-10-07 16:33:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

That one example didn't cut & paste properly. Trying again:

$ nova quota-delete
usage: nova quota-delete --tenant <tenant-id> [--user <user-id>]
error: argument --tenant is required"}, {'account_id': 16907, 'date': '2015-10-07 16:40:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Well that's frustrating (the formatting in the comment).

Here's the command line example using pastebin instead:

    http://paste.openstack.org/show/475635/

Note that it says 'tenant' is "optional" in the first help message, but "required" in the second help message.

And that's using `required=True`.'}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2015-10-07 17:13:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Diana: You can indent examples in your comments to get proper formatting:

    $ nova quota-delete
    usage: nova quota-delete --tenant <tenant-id> [--user <user-id>]
    error: argument --tenant is required'}, {'account_id': 16907, 'date': '2015-10-07 17:14:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Much better. Thanks a ton, Kevin!'}, {'account_id': 18494, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:10:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Another approach is that we can check whether flavor is specified or not before [1] to avoid unnecessary image available check. Please let me know your suggestion on the same.


[1] https://github.com/openstack/python-novaclient/blob/master/novaclient/v2/shell.py#L153'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-10-23 12:30:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

@ravi - I'd like that check before image approach better

@diana - whether upstream python believes in required args doesn't mean that they aren't required here. Flavor definitely is during boot.

@kevin - positional args only really make sense if they are of the same type. Otherwise they require far too much thinking, and are likely to get fat fingered in scripts. So I really don't want to go to positional args here."}, {'account_id': 18494, 'date': '2015-10-27 06:22:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-27 06:28:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

[{'created': '2015-10-05 11:47:19.000000000', 'message': 'Add required=True in flavor option

For boot command flavor option is mandatory. Currently this is checked
using if condition. A better way of doing this check is to add
required=True to flavor config option (arg decorator).This is
also the more efficient way as it will avoid unnecessary image
available check

Closes bug: #1502866
Change-Id: Ic68690b3d985d78ba0312bf5421989ccba7ceea8

commit_message:
Check flavor option before image checks

Currently flavor option is checked after performing the image checks
which results in unnecessary image checks even if flavor option is
not passed at all. Moved flavor option check at the beginning of the
method to eliminate the expensive operations performed as part of
image check.

Closes-Bug: #1502866
Change-Id: Ic68690b3d985d78ba0312bf5421989ccba7ceea8

commit_message:
Functional tests for os-extended-server-attributes

The added tests check basic set of extended server attributes
and additional attributes exposed by microversion 2.3

To avoid leak resources, cleanup part has been refactored

[{'created': '2015-10-05 18:34:58.000000000', 'message': 'CLI support for VPNaaS multiple local subnets

This provides CLI support for the new multiple local subnet feature, where the
user can specify endpoint groups (subnets for local, CIDRs for peer) and then
specify them in the IPSec site connection create.

Three CLIs are changed. The VPN service create CLI will now allow the subnet
argument to be optional. This will not be specified when mulitple local
subnets with endpoint groups are used.

The IPSec site to site connection create/update CLIs will now accept local and
peer endpoint group IDs/names, and the peer-cidr argument (deprecated) will
be optional.

Checks are done on create, to ensure that when endpoint groups are used (the
normal case), both local and peer group IDs/names are specified, and that
peer CIDR and endpoint groups are mutually exclusive. The server will check
whether peer CIDR or endpoint groups are used (via subnet specification on
VPN service).

For syntax of the endpoint groups in the IPSec connection command, there are
several choices, including the following (showing 'local' only, but 'peer'
would be similar):

    --local-epg <name/ID>
    --local-ep-group <name/ID>
    --local-endpoint-group <name/ID>

For now, --local-ep-group and --peer-ep-group was chosen, hopefully as a
balance between being descriptive and terse naming.

For the list CLI removed the peer CIDR field, which will normally be empty
now, and removed the route mode, which is hard-coded to "static" (and pretty
much useless info).

This, along with the server changes, provides the basic feature for multiple
local subnets.

Depends-On: I7a011e3170d7db463a6561e550b2ead3e3311125
Closes-Bug: 1459423
DocImpact

Change-Id: I2338d3478ad57da112fe34e83e131d94faf8bbcd

Checks are done on create, to ensure that when endpoint groups are used (the
normal case), both local and peer group IDs/names are specified, and that
peer CIDR and endpoint groups are mutually exclusive. The server will check
whether peer CIDR or endpoint groups are used (via subnet specification on
VPN service).

For syntax of the endpoint groups in the IPSec connection command, there are
several choices, including the following (showing 'local' only, but 'peer'
would be similar):

    --local-epg <name/ID>
    --local-ep-group <name/ID>
    --local-endpoint-group <name/ID>

For now, --local-ep-group and --peer-ep-group was chosen, hopefully as a
balance between being descriptive and terse naming.

For the list CLI removed the peer CIDR field, which will normally be empty
now, and removed the route mode, which is hard-coded to "static" (and pretty
much useless info).

This, along with the server changes, provides the basic feature for multiple
local subnets.

Depends-On: I7a011e3170d7db463a6561e550b2ead3e3311125
Closes-Bug: 1459423
DocImpact

commit_message:
CLI support for VPNaaS multiple local subnets

This provides CLI support for the new multiple local subnet feature, where the
user can specify endpoint groups (subnets for local, CIDRs for peer) and then
specify them in the IPSec site connection create.

Three CLIs are changed. The VPN service create CLI will now allow the subnet
argument to be optional. This will not be specified when mulitple local
subnets with endpoint groups are used.

The IPSec site to site connection create/update CLIs will now accept local and
peer endpoint group IDs/names, and the peer-cidr argument (deprecated) will
be optional.

Checks are done on create, to ensure that when endpoint groups are used (the
normal case), both local and peer group IDs/names are specified, and that
peer CIDR and endpoint groups are mutually exclusive. The server will check
whether peer CIDR or endpoint groups are used (via subnet specification on
VPN service).

For syntax of the endpoint groups in the IPSec connection command, there are
several choices, including the following (showing 'local' only, but 'peer'
would be similar):

    --local-epg <name/ID>
    --local-ep-group <name/ID>
    --local-endpoint-group <name/ID>

For now, --local-ep-group and --peer-ep-group was chosen, hopefully as a
balance between being descriptive and terse naming.

For the list CLI removed the peer CIDR field, which will normally be empty
now, and removed the route mode, which is hard-coded to "static" (and pretty
much useless info).

This, along with the server changes, provides the basic feature for multiple
local subnets.

Depends-On: I7a011e3170d7db463a6561e550b2ead3e3311125
Closes-Bug: 1459423
DocImpact

Change-Id: I2338d3478ad57da112fe34e83e131d94faf8bbcd

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "Remove Cisco-specific neutron client commands""

This reverts commit 716eb017d35829c18745c4c0279b895784c297f1.

The original commit 8292cb85f8830e65284736ea1f9bae2f344c084a had to
be reverted since it needed a client version bump to 4.x. This commit
reverts that revert.

Change-Id: Ib936b9ee4ac16089153209e60c05ed477731fd77

[{'created': '2015-11-06 11:26:00.000000000', 'message': "cells: Create BDM only when device_name is not null

There is currently a race in test_create_ebs_image_and_check_boot which
does the following:

1. Create a volume.
2. Boot a server instance using that volume.
3. Snapshot the volume-backed server instance.
4. Boot a second server from the snapshot image.

The second server boot fails because the snapshot image has duplicate
BDM snapshot entries with the same boot_index in it's metadata. This is
because there is a race on the initial server boot from volume where
cells_api.bdm_update_or_create_at_top is called in quick succession. Both
come from BlockDeviceMapping.save(). One comes from the compute manager when
prepping block devices during the instance build, and one from the virt layer
when the libvirt driver code nulls out the device_name on the BDM and saves
that off to the database. bdm_update_or_create_at_top is racing to update the
first BDM and ends up creating a second BDM instead, which then ends up
being turned into two volume snapshots in step 3 above.

So the root issue is the race in bdm_update_or_create_at_top and knowing when
we should be doing an insert versus an update. We should be able to determine
this based on when the device_name is set on the BDM rather than simply being
changed.

This change aims to discriminate whether it's a create or an update by looking
at the device_name. If the device_name is not None, then it's a create, else
it's just a DB update.

That's yet another compelling patch for trying to fix the gate issue.

Co-Authored-By: Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dms@danplanet.com>

Change-Id: I6ce2e43cc0c4c0e1cac8c9e2e107f55675c898dc
Closes-Bug: #1489581

commit_message:
cells: Create BDM only when device_name is not null

There is currently a race in test_create_ebs_image_and_check_boot which
does the following:

1. Create a volume.
2. Boot a server instance using that volume.
3. Snapshot the volume-backed server instance.
4. Boot a second server from the snapshot image.

The second server boot fails because the snapshot image has duplicate
BDM snapshot entries with the same boot_index in it's metadata. This is
because there is a race on the initial server boot from volume where
cells_api.bdm_update_or_create_at_top is called in quick succession. Both
come from BlockDeviceMapping.save(). One comes from the compute manager when
prepping block devices during the instance build, and one from the virt layer
when the libvirt driver code nulls out the device_name on the BDM and saves
that off to the database. bdm_update_or_create_at_top is racing to update the
first BDM and ends up creating a second BDM instead, which then ends up
being turned into two volume snapshots in step 3 above.

So the root issue is the race in bdm_update_or_create_at_top and knowing when
we should be doing an insert versus an update. We should be able to determine
this based on when the device_name is set on the BDM rather than simply being
changed.

This change aims to discriminate whether it's a create or an update by looking
at the device_name. If the device_name is not None, then it's a create, else
it's just a DB update.

That's yet another compelling patch for trying to fix the gate issue.

Co-Authored-By: Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dms@danplanet.com>

Change-Id: I6ce2e43cc0c4c0e1cac8c9e2e107f55675c898dc

Fix Windows batch script library location

updated to reflect the new name. Fixed.

commit_message:
Network configuration update should return 400

In case of raising exception 'OutOfIPs' Nailgun should return 400 error.

* Add exception catching for 'errors.OutOfIPs' in 'ProviderHandler.PUT'.
* Add corresponding unit test.

Change-Id: I7018621350651a351c164fe45a72001874b11e57
Partial-bug: #1513774

"}, {'created': '2015-09-09 12:37:39.000000000', 'message': "Invalid output running the command 'glance image-show <image_id>'

Running the command returns the string 'id' and fails on exception.
In function _image_meta_from_headers the meta variable was not properly
set because key was not lowercased. Converting key to lowercase solves

commit_message:
Invalid output running the command 'glance image-show <image_id>'

Running the command returns the string 'id' and fails on exception.
In function _image_meta_from_headers the meta variable was not properly
set because key was not lowercased. Converting key to lowercase solves
the problem.

NOTE: this is a compatibility fix for urllib3 >= 1.11

Closes-Bug: #1487645
Co-Authored-by: Flavio Percoco <flavio@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I1b0b327163577585becb5e762536058d21dc1c98

commit_message:
fix freezer-db-init modifies replicas in test mode

The freezer-db-init command was changing the replica number
of the elasticsearch freezer index even in test mode.

Now it correctly returns an error when in invoked in test mode
and the replica number is different from the expected value.

Change-Id: I290b47b5e76c94f16c73cfc0d47d3859d4495063

commit_message:
Add iptables rule to listen m-api

Bay will request Magnum API to get certificates, so
$MAGNUM_SERVICE_PORT must be opened.
This patch adds this rule to `devstack/lib/magnum`
instead of `magnum/tests/contrib/post_test_hook.sh`.

Ironic also adds same rules in devstack[1].

[1]: https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/blob/master/lib/ironic#L675

Change-Id: I24baf87475044a7f268811080b25032152152c39
Closes-Bug: #1515478

commit_message:
Add support for 2048bit ssl certificate to HAproxy

In the current HAproxy configuration support only 1024bit ssl
certificate without warnings.
Modify the configuration to support 2048bit certificate.

Change-Id: I87dfd4c7ea56b5f432d324d02c63ee020a5f2a7f
Closes-bug: #1514904

commit_message:
Block oslo.messaging 2.8.0

There is a locking regression in the 2.8.0 release that is
causing nova unit/functional tests to time out.

Depends-On: #I37eeb57e99db5f77a11eed471ac6c55c4547e821

Change-Id: I3ec6a6429bb1032e47fb0317ce9ca4b769666370
Closes-Bug: #1514876

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-11 17:09:14.000000000', 'message': "Fix supervisorctl interactions for restore

Currently we are always attempting to stop a container in supervisord
without checking that supervisord is actually running. This can lead to
issues where attempting issue a supervisorctl stop while the supervisord
process is stopping. Since we are shutting down the supervisord process
when we do a restore, we can get into a state where the container stop
will actually fail the restore.

This change adds a check to get the supervisord PID to check if it's
running before issuing a supervisorctl stop command. Additionally this
change adds a 60 second sleep after the shutdown of supervisord (as
recommended by supervisord). This sleep will allow the child processes
to exit cleanly and the socket file will be properly cleaned up.

Change-Id: Ic10036109afb26083c60791dd09a71262784e159
Closes-Bug: #1514798

commit_message:
Fix supervisorctl interactions for restore

Currently we are always attempting to stop a container in supervisord
without checking that supervisord is actually running. This can lead to
issues where attempting issue a supervisorctl stop while the supervisord
process is stopping. Since we are shutting down the supervisord process
when we do a restore, we can get into a state where the container stop
will actually fail the restore.

This change adds a check to get the supervisord PID to check if it's
running before issuing a supervisorctl stop command. Additionally this
change adds a timed sleep check after the shutdown of supervisord (as
recommended by supervisord). This sleep will allow the child processes
to exit cleanly and the socket file will be properly cleaned up.

Change-Id: Ic10036109afb26083c60791dd09a71262784e159
Closes-Bug: #1514798

commit_message:
Pin docker version for atomic at 1.8.2

docker-latest now points to 1.9.0, which isn't the version we're
targetting. More importantly, docker-1.9.0 doesn't work since it
complains about /etc not being able to be relabeled. Not sure how to fix
that, but we can save that battle for another time.

Change-Id: I947b7569d9cf40a409253336e51b4dec5ada36f8

commit_message:

commit_message:
remove redundant character '/' about epel url

Avoiding redundant '/' after epel at etc/yum.repos.d/base.repo
like "baseurl=http://mirror.yandex.ru/epel//6/x86_64/" in SANDBOX.

commit_message:
Untie subobject versions

Since obj_relationships was removed in
Iea8b6348e3b01aaa335ec5408f07826f1e758d20 because manifest backports are
now used, most parent object versions will no longer change when a child
object is changed. Because of this, some objects that have a child
version tied to a parent version no longer need to be tied. The versions
can progress individually on their own. The child is all grown up now,
he's moving out of his parents' basement, buying a car, and going on to
make his parents proud.

Change-Id: Ie0c7bd419e3490d01f73c7a39cd2666eafcf9539

commit_message:
Adding back the git clone requirements

pip constrains is from requirements repo, but change in devstack
I42e981c8c5ce1b8a57b9f6cce213065c72d6af11a removed the requirements
clone from install_infra, causing the grenade "pip_install -U pbr" fail.
Make changes for grenade accordingly.

Change-Id: Ie228bd9399c5cc9341cc5503f02df90eb42d851f
Closes-bug: #1487259

commit_message:
Revert "Store correct VirtCPUTopology"

This reverts commit 8358936a24cd223046580ddfa3bfb37a943abc91.

The bug patch being reverted was trying to fix is not a bug bug at all
but is actually by design. The NUMA cell CPU
topology was meant to carry information about threads that we want to
expose to the single cell based on how it was fitted with regards to
threading on the host, so that we can expose this information to the
guest OS if possible for optimal performance.

The final topology exposed to the guest takes this information into
account as well as any request for particular topology passed in by the
user and decides on the final solution. There is no reason to store this
as it will be different for different hosts.

We want to revert this as it is really not something that we want to be
doing, and will make it easier to cleanly fix 1501358.

Change-Id: Iae06c468c076337b9d6e85d0d0dc85a063b827d1
Partial-bug: 1501358
Partial-bug: 1467927

partially-implements: blueprint incremental-backup
'}, {'created': '2014-09-04 11:23:02.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for backups to xiv_ds8k driver

commit_message:
Add support for backups to xiv_ds8k driver

Adds the functions backup_volume and restore_backup to xiv_ds8k cinder driver.
Provides support for full backup.

Implements: blueprint xiv-ds8k-backup
Change-Id: Ib8ea2f6698e23552dea2e093b8615a89f162c50d

commit_message:
Support all_tenants search_opts for neutron

Add support for the all_tenants search option when listing
security group with neutron as the backend

The neutron doesn't have `all-tenants` concept. All the security
groups will be returned if the project/tenant id is not passed.

Conflicts:
        nova/network/security_group/neutron_driver.py
        nova/tests/unit/network/security_group/test_neutron_driver.py

NOTE(mriedem): The unit tests were moved in kilo and I had to import
mock. The code conflict is due to commit 4bab641e9.

Change-Id: I465c946a006aca21b298f8226f55725a8c36c1f8
Co-authored-by: Xurong Yang <yangxurong@huawei.com>
closes-bug: #1284202
(cherry picked from commit 5da4a317086e6c9d6620d1bd686bc53923006904)
(cherry picked from commit 69a4ca0a83f1fb0a457448ba68a81d7cc3429cc4)

[{'created': '2015-10-26 16:47:58.000000000', 'message': "Port share actions to core API

Changes:
- Register share actions API as core API.
- Remove extension code for share actions.
- Leave rename of share actions API 'put' data for future update which
  will be done with bump of microversion

commit_message:
Port share actions to core API

Changes:
- Register share actions API as core API.
- Remove extension code for share actions.
- Leave rename of share actions API 'put' data for future update which
  will be done with bump of microversion
  after port of all extensions to core API.

Partially implements bp ext-to-core

Change-Id: I7fef38c37ae539473b6e3d2a0758c336b2a7d33c

commit_message:
Replace all StackForge names to OpenStack

spec_helpers didn't change because keystone module (>=5.1.0 <6.0.0)
is not present in openstack/keystone - only >= 6.0.0 and it will
not working for puppet-ceph acceptance tests, because they are running
with Juno code.

Change-Id: Ibf7c55cac755432fb4901587693363cea4c27f42

I know this is a nit, but I'm not a big fan of a *required* config file in the command line - can we have a default config file that can be overridden at the command line?"}, {'account_id': 17995, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:57:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 9189, 'date': '2015-11-12 04:00:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@ryan: I actually thought about having a default value there, but I didn't want to add it without consulting what a decent default value would be.

I'd suggest to add a default config file in another patch and keep this one as it is, since it keeps the same behavior; then we can change the behavior in a later patch actually adding the default config.

commit_message:
Add command line args to api.py

When called without the config file path, api.py would just raise an
IndexError exception. This makes it a bit more resilient by adding a
required config_file option to the command line.

As a nice side-effect, it also adds a nice helper text allowing the
user/developer to know what's expected in order to successfully run the
API service, either by passing -h, --help, or by not suplying the
config file.

Co-Authored-By: Dhiana Deva <ddeva@thoughtworks.com>
Change-Id: I17aebb01beef8ce7701077924d5146c4de6a47f2

commit_message:
Refactor variable naming and removes underscore.js

This commit normalize variable naming on job controller, as well on its
viem. As part of it I removed the dependency on underscore.js.

commit_message:
Use oslo.service for launching sahara

Changes:
* use launcher for running sahara modules
* use wsgi server from oslo.service library

Change-Id: I9ba8f1e751ce9bb9b9adcebda6509107b98e2fc8

commit_message:
Add tags to .gitignore

When using ctags, it will provide a 'tags' file in the directory.
It should be added to .gitignore.

Change-Id: If393c934a72397e755fc9e9672bb8d610d589a83

The `nova-manage db archive_deleted_rows` command doesn't print any

passed a --verbose option.

Implements blueprint print-table-archived-rows

commit_message:
Print number of rows archived per table in db archive_deleted_rows

The `nova-manage db archive_deleted_rows` command doesn't print any
results, not even how many rows were deleted, which is something the
database API returns.

The number of rows deleted also changes depending on the max_rows input
and how many rows are deleted in each table, it's a cumulative effect.

We should keep track of which tables we've deleted rows from along with
how many rows, and print that all out to the CLI console if the user
passed a --verbose option.

Implements blueprint print-table-archived-rows

Change-Id: I5c47cd5633eca056f8ae508753a41e2c1ed9e523

Support multiple IPv6 prefixes on router ports

commit_message:
Initial instructrions for stable/liberty repos

The new stable/liberty repos should now be built via the RDO
centos7-liberty delorean repos, so document using these to enable
deploying the current stable branches.

Change-Id: Id1f7f3c121a17c31a0009ea71bccda18b12ca03f

commit_message:
Fix test class docstring for py 3.5

Add a docstring to TestCommand so we get that one instead of inheriting
the one from the base class. In previous versions the docstring was not
inherited, but that has changed.

Change-Id: I90c808836f4f7651df89734ace32dcf62a351525
Related-bug: #1491888

commit_message:
Remove get_all method from servicegroup API

Change Idc0dfbbe1887e11166acb7d989dd5466751761af removed
get_all method from mc and db drivers, and made this
method private in zk driver.

Now no one of servicegroup drivers (mc, db, zk) doesn't
implement method get_all. And it's very confusing.

This method used nowhere so it should be removed.

Closes-Bug: #1502107

Change-Id: Ie56d15f61aa61e3bd05c77eab52c65d557de5d8b

commit_message:
Fix the help text of monkey_patch config param

The help text of monkey_patch config param was misleading as it
referred to logging but the code used this param to turn on the whole
monkey patching in nova.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ie1700ca5ab781354eda7e88577423a8f0b21f264
Closes-Bug: #1491446

commit_message:
Remove useless get_instance_faults()

Instance faults is filled in Instance object, so
compute.api.get_instance_faults() isn't called by
any code logic. Remove it and related test cases.

Change-Id: I6309ab114246bd5a98c238ad6965f9a9bbeee437

commit_message:
Check shellinabox process during stopping console

Currently we assume shellinabox is running as long as pid file
exists, which will cause error while executing kill command,
this patch update to use os.kill() and if errno is ESRCH, just
log a warning message.

Change-Id: Ib8968418a1835a4131f2f22fb3e4df5ecb9b0dc5
Closes-Bug: #1513690

commit_message:
Fetch and return SCSI WWN

This patch adds the SCSI WWN for iSCSI and FC based volumes
in the return for connect_volume calls.   This WWN can be used
to uniquely identify the volume.

Change-Id: Ic98cdd700bc9fa3467e8c7f3cdaa70c12414ad75
Implements: blueprint brick-scsi-wwn

commit_message:
Avoid requesting get-pip.py multiple times

This patch prevents the contents of get-pip.py from being printed to the
console and it avoids retrieving the script more than once via curl unless
absolutely necessary.

Closes-bug: 1514988

Change-Id: I6b312dfac23c8b32dba71edcfc65f65858349893

commit_message:
Add magnum support to functional tests on shade

Enable magnum plugin, so we can start adding magnum functionality
and tests for it.
Also increasing timeout, as magnum tests can cause more overhead.

Change-Id: I6e400584202d2d8dbfbd864e2f1941b7a2dc74ce

commit_message:
Remove openstack-dashboard-apache package

This change adds the removal of the openstack-dashboard-apache package
as it conflicts with our configuration of apache via the openstack
puppet-horizon class.

Change-Id: I3e4dc65380a3197654be49a911853d67b6a20659
Partial-Bug: #1513252

It would be useful to have a spec in place so we can talk about the requirements, so please start by writing up something for oslo-specs.
