commit_message:
Pretty print list of commands

Because prettytable is already a requirement of cliff it should
be used to pretty print a table of all available commands. This
will also easify it to parse the list of commands inside other
tools like the openstack-doc-tools.

Example output without this change:

Commands:
  aggregate add host  Add host to aggregate
  aggregate create  Create a new aggregate
  aggregate delete  Delete an existing aggregate
  aggregate list  List all aggregates
  aggregate remove host  Remove host from aggregate
  aggregate set  Set aggregate properties
  aggregate show  Show a specific aggregate
  backup create  Create backup command
  backup delete  Delete backup command
  backup list    List backup command
  backup restore  Restore backup command
  backup show    Show backup command
...

Example output with this change:

The following commands are available:
+------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------+
| Command                      | Description                                   |
+------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------+
| aggregate add host           | Add host to aggregate                         |
| aggregate create             | Create a new aggregate                        |
| aggregate delete             | Delete an existing aggregate                  |
| aggregate list               | List all aggregates                           |
| aggregate remove host        | Remove host from aggregate                    |
| aggregate set                | Set aggregate properties                      |
| aggregate show               | Show a specific aggregate                     |
| backup create                | Create backup command                         |
| backup delete                | Delete backup command                         |
| backup list                  | List backup command                           |
| backup restore               | Restore backup command                        |
| backup show                  | Show backup command                           |
...

Change-Id: I6c353bee40d111c9362381796e849a880da5649d

commit_message:
Provide locking around NPIV wwpns method

If the user runs two attach volumes at the same time, this can lead to a
race condition where different WWPNs get generated for the instance.
This change provides a lock around the wwpns call.  This is a global
lock for the compute node.

In previous iterations of this code, it could have had a major
performance impact.  But now that the job is invoked for the WWPNs call,
this method should return very quickly (subsecond).  Therefore the
global lock should not be a concern.

Change-Id: I4100e5c66797eb4f1fad802a88ef90966a05ce13
Closes-Bug: 1514537

commit_message:
Add middleware for external requests

New middleware will solve the problem with non-Openstack requests by
adding some minimal required headers.

Change-Id: I49986e73d0eb3da1ce13d22771c6bcb5a28ba846
Implements: bp external-request-middleware

commit_message:
Document token provider support

Only the uuid provider is tested in the gate, so is the only one
that should be documented as supported.

Fernet tokens are currently not passing the tempest tests and are
not part of the gate tests, so the provider should be clearly
marked as experimental.

Change-Id: Ib62c61dac4acf832672a845cceeaf3486b9e5cd5
Closes-Bug: 1496998

commit_message:
Detect not-started _TransactionFactory in legacy

When LegacyEngineFacade is passed a _TransactionFactory
that is not started, or one that fails to start, the
_start() method should be called again each time the
factory is called upon; this ensures that the failed
start either can be made to succeed, or at least re-raises
the same error as earlier, instead of falling into attribute
access for non-existent attributes.

Change-Id: I7484f837d455c1f69c448e5ccadc277d19af47e7
Closes-Bug: #1515326

commit_message:
Properly wrap unplug errors

When an unplug_vif error occurs, it needs to be wrapped in a
NovaException so that the manager takes the right action.  This change
set properly wraps errors in the unplug_vifs.

Change-Id: I53928b80ec6d38063194ad06e3c89784bb8365ca
Closes-Bug: 1514437

[{'created': '2015-11-10 11:55:07.000000000', 'message': 'Properly order node deletion from cache

In databases that actually support foreign keys (like MySQL),
we need to delete everything linking to a node before deleting a node.

Change-Id: I320d8547697c3c13b7acb2e3fee117347550e264
Closes-Bug: #1511187
'}]
commit_message:
Properly order node deletion from cache

In databases that actually support foreign keys (like MySQL),
we need to delete everything linking to a node before deleting a node.

Change-Id: I320d8547697c3c13b7acb2e3fee117347550e264
Closes-Bug: #1511187

commit_message:
Adding Identity NGProjects Angular API

This patch adds the angular client for the rest api,
needed mainly for the quota-related actions in the angular
identity projects panel.

Change-Id: I5a14b012ba872c37a89483ab5be16372123b2af2
Partially-Implements: blueprint angularize-identity-projects

commit_message:
Add method to get a mounted session from config

Getting a session is great, but sometimes you need a thing called
an "adapter" which takes 5 parameters which are all already contained in
the config that you used to get the session.

Change-Id: Id4e418cd04ae81540d9898f7b2e959b974f355d2

commit_message:
Fix bogus pip install URI in tox_install.sh

The branch specification was misplaced.
This only impacted test run locally by a developer.

Change-Id: I55671d7a9c7df501048febe24a15ba5f55a33024

commit_message:
Remove unneeded workaround for ksc

It turns out keystoneclient can take string input and does the
same transform we're doing here, it's just not documented. Remove the
workaround on our side as it's unneccesary.

Change-Id: Ie46945f7d96e3d65004cd19823b3be989e1d18a7

commit_message:
add "unreleased" release notes page

We need a release notes page to show notes for unreleased versions by
scanning the "current" branch. This ensures that notes files cannot be
merged if they break the releasenotes job.

Change-Id: I5d3fbf8e4ba724ee97d668250d129e80c7486e1b
(cherry picked from commit d92201ff6fb6bda857d23ee34f1d9ae5addb0e77)

commit_message:
Drop root privileges for mariadb

Drop root privileges for mariadb.  This isn't perfect.  If somemone
breaks out of the container and can run sudo within the contianer,
it would be possible to replace the root credentials of the database.

Any container that uses sudo suffers from some extra attack vector
related to the sudo command.  That said, the sudo commands are
locked down to minimize harm.

Change-Id: I4b3573725d940bb8aa90d43a6235d8cf7d30fc64
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
Adding docs/comments for glance config

Deployers who use a dollar sign ($) in their swift backend passwords for glance
will be unable to authenticate to the swift backend. This is due to how
oslo.config formats strings.  This patch adds documentation and comments to
the user_variables.yml to ensure deployers know how to escape those strings.

This patch also adds a commented variable for the auth version on swift
backends so that deployers are reminded to use the correct version number.

Closes-bug: 1514291

Change-Id: I717e9afb5af1160de67dc5d0f87985fde5ad393e
(cherry picked from commit 1f4996bdd93914b9533c1e9931aca92d1ae56295)

commit_message:
Fix race condition for /openstack directories

To resolve a possible race condition when containers are creating
log directories the /openstack directory and its basic sub-directories
are being created within the openstack_hosts role which will ensure that
the appropriate skeleton is available when the containers go to build
in subsequent tasks.

Closes-bug: #1426254
Change-Id: Icdbddf285f8b898518657b082a9263a2923c97c4
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit de6f3a21e04daff5ea583653bef6ed62de624635)

commit_message:
Reference correct group in haproxy_config.yml

Currently, playbooks/vars/configs/haproxy_config.yml references group
metering-alarm_all, however this group is not defined in
etc/openstack_deploy/env.d.  This commit updates haproxy_config.yml
to use service group aodh_api instead.

Closes-Bug: #1512676

Change-Id: I93ac55edb15130cd1afa069a638f724be91cbe3b

commit_message:
Symlink ceph libraries out of venv

Currently, we install python-rados and python-rbd via apt when ceph
integration is enabled, which causes issues when venvs are used in the
environment.  This commit adds a temporary work-around by creating
symlinks in the venv to the installed libraries outside.

There is currently a ceph issue [1] in progress to make this possible,
and once this has been completed we can update ceph_client role to
install python packages instead.

[1] http://tracker.ceph.com/issues/5900

Change-Id: Ia7a3ceae002054fd75e0305892b20ce1143f8dcc
Closes-Bug: #1509837

commit_message:
Add ability to configure paste ini options using config class

  It is needed in order to have possibility to add custom api options
  without direct usage of config providers in manifests.

Change-Id: I3e4a2ba175d6974ba4c4fb170aa663d15cb8467a

commit_message:
Split SR-IOV configuration file into driver and agent pieces

On Liberty the configuration files for SR-IOV split into agent and
driver, also they are now stored on a specific directory.

Change-Id: I8d4e2fda6beb1d7dac77fa1fbb9bbbbe3432a3ef

commit_message:
Implement subunit_parser

subunit2json module was implemented based on subunit2html module, which
cause several issues(see attached bugs for more details).

The main approach of new parser: it designed to be used from Python code,
not as live-filter for a stream.

Since such parser can be used not only for verification, the implementation
is moved to common dir.

Also, this patch:
 - removes fake log, which was left from xml parser;
 - removes all db calls(except list call) from cli.verify module.

Closes-Bug: #1456810
Closes-Bug: #1471400
Change-Id: Ifcfce827a0df1e75f58e198ee899d4bb85ca9376

commit_message:
Hook for live-migration job

Live-migration multinode job should check different configurations.
To implement this new hook in nova should be used. Current patch adds
execution of live-migration specific use-cases.

Change-Id: I3ad9287b8f103a874f88100df82fa9e1f8617d6f

commit_message:
Add missing policy rules

Added a LOG.info nova.policy:enforce method to print
what exactly we are testing in our gate jobs (see
I62d8572e36b8ebb5ece218d858679e93ca0f8c7e) and found
these two rules were missing.

Change-Id: I94780b5173a72c93cf3f7e0dabd429f40fcda46f

commit_message:
Remove duplicate keys in policy.json

In I8d58be7f3cb1bdefc3b783a256c21ed216cdbad7, we added
"compute:delete", "compute:soft_delete" and "compute:force_delete",
So let's remove the older lines that have the an empty "" target.

Change-Id: I239ca596cca4631e311d7afe45de7ffcc60f70b9

commit_message:
Fix DVR downgrade exception / error code

Updating a distributed router back to a legacy router
should return error 400 (BadRequest), not error 500.

Closes-Bug: #1505346
Change-Id: Ia57e80107bd11ff7b38b89d30279603017913724
(cherry picked from commit a6d9580f2b95bf2c7c607d4e2671ffbbceae28d5)

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Adds Hyper-V UEFI Secure Boot

Hyper-V supports UEFI SecureBoot since the 2012 R2 version
for Windows guests and this has been extended to Linux
guests as well with the upcoming release.

Change-Id: Ibc80496e9ea5f0961db38140e647d7c2c4c328c6
Partially-Implements: blueprint hyper-v-uefi-secureboot

commit_message:
Remove tempdir config, add tempdir parameter

This removes the tempdir config because it is only being used by
one method. Instead, disk_utils.work_on_disk() was modified to
include a tempdir parameter.

Change-Id: Ic91bce4ebe295c79fb7303bba2c4a2390f4d4a53
Closes-Bug: #1514613

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-24 08:43:15.000000000', 'message': 'Split network plane for live migration

Now data transfer of live migration occupy the management
network of openstack deployment. In the KVM/QEMU driver,
we use hostname of target compute node in
CONF.libvirt.live_migration_uri, so rpc call and data
transfer of live migration will be in same network plane,
live migration will impact the network performance,
the impact is obvious when lots of live migration occur
at the same time.

This blueprint purposed to split network plane of live
migration, the operators can plan a specify network plane
for live migration and split it from management network.

DocImpact

Co-Authored-By: Zhenyu Zheng <zhengzhenyu@huawei.com>

blueprint split-network-plane-for-live-migration

Change-Id: If089e269718fa8fdcf3728f3d030960015356f81
'}, {'created': '2015-06-25 09:06:28.000000000', 'message': 'Split network plane for live migration

commit_message:
Split network plane for live migration

Now data transfer of live migration occupy the management
network of openstack deployment. In the KVM/QEMU driver,
we use hostname of target compute node in
CONF.libvirt.live_migration_uri, so rpc call and data
transfer of live migration will be in same network plane,
live migration will impact the network performance,
the impact is obvious when lots of live migration occur
at the same time.

This specification purposed to split network plane of live
migration, the operators can plan a specify network plane
for live migration and split it from management network.

DocImpact

Co-Authored-By: Zhenyu Zheng <zhengzhenyu@huawei.com>

blueprint split-network-plane-for-live-migration

Change-Id: If089e269718fa8fdcf3728f3d030960015356f81

commit_message:
More graceful ovs-agent restart

When the neutron server is down/busy the agent is not able to get any
port info. After the agent restarts, it will not install any new flow.
Cleaning the existing flows will break all networking until the agent
succeeds to sync with the neturon server.

This patch ensures the agent cleans the stale flows only after it
succeeds to sync with the neturon server.

Change-Id: I763fc06a73b6d2f010da65e74241182636dda44d
Closes-bug: #1515075

commit_message:
Improve rally.common.utils.RAMInt code

*) There is no need to create extra lock object. There is already
   instance of lock object in multiprocessing.Value

*) Improve the tests. Unit tests should test that method properly
   work and not mock everything to check what is in each python line
   (which is anti pattern in unit testing)

Change-Id: I7cc102aae0e083e2fccf98cbc21f8f43cef8d454

commit_message:
Wait for container SSH

This adds a wait condition when creating the containers to ensure
that the containers are created correctly and that ssh is available
within them before actually continuing with the installation process

Change-Id: I78926651ea7a0cdfd6d903c590b421448264a4fb

While we're in the process of updating a stack, we set the stack's
environment to the new, updated values. However, we don't want to change
existing resources' idea of their own values until we have explivitly done
an update of them to bring them into line with the new
template/environment. So when parsing a template snippet containing the
get_file intrinsic, store the files dict to which it will refer. get_file
will resolve to the new file only when the template has been updated.

commit_message:
Don't re-bind environment for get_file during stack update

While we're in the process of updating a stack, we set the stack's
environment to the new, updated values. However, we don't want to change
existing resources' idea of their own values until we have explivitly done
an update of them to bring them into line with the new
template/environment. So when parsing a template snippet containing the
get_file intrinsic, store the files dict to which it will refer. get_file
will resolve to the new file only when the template has been updated.

Closes-Bug: #1445170
Change-Id: I8ec32b0e38389cd314e4b2b2d8c65f61f8a9c41e
(cherry picked from commit e4447e7b66cf4691218b067643b5e25de72e31ba)

[{'created': '2015-10-16 14:08:04.000000000', 'message': "Fix testing issues

When functional tests are run in tox and an exception is raised when connecting
to Swift (for example: Swift not running, missing python-keystoneclient package
used by python-swiftclient) 0 tests are executed, but tox returns a success.

An exception is raised during tests, caused by a missing python-keystoneclient
in python-swiftclient. Instead of adding python-keystoneclient as a dependency
in python-swiftclient the package is added to the test-requirements.txt in Swift
itself. Note that adding python-keystoneclient to the test-requirements in
python-swiftclient is not sufficient (it's already in there).

The exception in setup_package() is catched by the openstack.nose_plugin, thus
disabling this plugin for now as well.

Also fixing two test errors seen on the gate regarding the tempurl middleware.

There was also an update to tox, environment variables were no longer passed
with versions >= 2.0 (http://tox.readthedocs.org/en/latest/changelog.html).
Swift test environment variables have been added to the passenv to re-enable the
former behavior, as well as environment variables required to pass proxy
settings.

This also led to skipped tempauth tests, and together with the missing
python-keystoneclient no tests were executed.

Related-Bug: 1461440
Related-Bug: 1455102

Co-Authored-By: Alistair Coles <alistair.coles@hp.com>

commit_message:
Fix testing issues

When functional tests are run in tox and an exception is raised when connecting
to Swift (for example: Swift not running, missing python-keystoneclient package
used by python-swiftclient) 0 tests are executed, but tox returns a success.

An exception is raised during tests, caused by a missing python-keystoneclient
in python-swiftclient. Instead of adding python-keystoneclient as a dependency
in python-swiftclient the package is added to the test-requirements.txt in Swift
itself. Note that adding python-keystoneclient to the test-requirements in
python-swiftclient is not sufficient (it's already in there).

The exception in setup_package() is catched by the openstack.nose_plugin, thus
disabling this plugin for now as well.

Also fixing two test errors seen on the gate regarding the tempurl middleware.

There was also an update to tox, environment variables were no longer passed
with versions >= 2.0 (http://tox.readthedocs.org/en/latest/changelog.html).
Swift test environment variables have been added to the passenv to re-enable the
former behavior, as well as environment variables required to pass proxy
settings.

This also led to skipped tempauth tests, and together with the missing
python-keystoneclient no tests were executed.

Related-Bug: 1461440
Related-Bug: 1455102

Co-Authored-By: Alistair Coles <alistair.coles@hp.com>

Change-Id: Ideea071017d04912c60ed0bc76532adbb446c31d
(cherry picked from commit f1f4bb30cd8ad930ddb7a232b2744b48e35a0480
with modified python-keystoneclient version specifiers in test-requirements.txt)

commit_message:
Adding HTML baseline formatter

This commit adds the HTML baseline formatter which works the same
as the the normal HTML formatter except it displays candidate
issues in the case where Bandit can't determine which is the
matching issue.

It also spiffs up the HTML report a bit.  Similar enhancements
to normal HTML reporting are coming in a subsequent patch.

Change-Id: Ic4fa9b81cea094e62850a9fefffba8e966145695

[{'created': '2015-11-06 13:12:45.000000000', 'message': "Adding the Text Baseline Formatter

This commit sets up using baseline formatters.  First we have to
check that the user has picked a support baseline output format
when they are using the baseline feature.  Assuming the user is
using a supported format and the baseline feature we'll
automatically pick the baseline version for them.

Baseline formatters are very similar to the normal version with

commit_message:
Adding the Text Baseline Formatter

This commit sets up using baseline formatters.  First we have to
check that the user has picked a support baseline output format
when they are using the baseline feature.  Assuming the user is
using a supported format and the baseline feature we'll
automatically pick the baseline version for them.

Baseline formatters are very similar to the normal version with
two changes.  First we don't output the code location for the
issue we found (since we don't know it).  Second, for each finding
we'll output a list of candidate findings with code location.  The
idea is that the user can pick out which of the candidates is the
actual new issue.

Change-Id: Ic91602ce7e9a970037113fec4b434c1554cf720b

commit_message:
New Theme Work Needs Better Documentation

A number of components of Horizon have been made theme-ready, but proper
documentation needs to follow to provide guidance of how to make use of
this new feature.

Change-Id: I8c95801eb0bfa6bd1692c794536e292c5478dd3d
Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-theme-css-reorg

subject: Add indexer to iterable objects
messages:
[{'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-11-03 09:52:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-11-03 13:02:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2015-11-04 11:27:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

The fact that indexer cannot be applied to iterable (read generator) was done intentionally. The reason is that any generator is forward-only. Imagine what will be the result of the following expression {a => $iter[2], b => $iter[0]}. Not only it depends on the order of execution but when evaluated from left to right (as it is) both a and b will have the same value despite different indexes! Because ability to index on iterables blurs the border between lists and iterables it will be surprising to most of the users. Lists and generators are very different it is wrong to pretend that iterable can be accessed as a list. Even in Python you cannot index on generator.

Regarding the bug and the use case: there are methods that addresses it already:
$iter.first()
$iter.skip(1).first()'}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-11-04 11:36:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Do we have cases when we access to the same generator twice in yaql? And I'm not sure that it is so obvious, that query function returns generator instead of collection, that can be indexed, at least from user perspective: if i apply some query function, for example `where`, i get a list as a result of evaluation. So what is the reason to forbid indexation in this case?"}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-11-04 12:51:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Agree, commit message can confuse, but i add indexer to iterable objects in internal implementation, in yaql itself it looks like applying index operator to usual list.
Is it possible to get a generator as a result of evaluation using yaql, so allowing to apply index to it will be bad thing? Doesn't see how to do it now and i'm wondering about how we can work with this generator if we get it.
Correct me if i'm wrong, i can miss some important concepts."}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2015-11-06 15:49:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Langauage must be consistent and work correctly in all cases. Neither you nor me know all use cases for the yaql and where it can be used in the future. The fact that in most real-life cases there will be no problem doesn't change the fact. Btw example above is close to what can be in real use case.

Also
1) Distinction between lists and iterators is fundamental and going to be documented. For example iterator can be endless
2) Indexation on list can be done with negative indexes like in Python. This is impossible to achieve on lists without iterating through  all iterator elements
3) You can always do that manually: list($myIterator)[2]
4) Most of the time you don't need indexer at all even for the lists. Even in python most of the time you either iterate over collection or take first element. yaql has methods for both. Cases when you need to access arbitrary element in list are relatively rare
5) Taking this in account most of the time user don't need to distinguish iterators from lists. He should always treat any collection as iterator even if it's really a list unless he knows exactly that the opposite is true. If I want to access collection as a list I'd better write list($collection) to convert it to list so that I won't need to remember how $collection is represented. In fact if $collection is already a list list() function will do nothing so no performance cost for that. When I want to get first element I always write $collection.first() even if I know that it is list because first() is more expressive and explicit. And also readable.
6) yaql is heavily inspired by the LINQ which doesn't has such feature. LINQ is a time-proven thing and I never heard someone had problems with it. Not mentioning my personal experience.
7) Explicit is better than implicit. Indexation on iterators has very different algorithmic complexity from that in the list. To make indexation possible yaql need to automatically convert iterator to list behind the scene and that is implicit action with performance cost. when user writes list($iterator)[$index] it becomes explicit"}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2015-11-06 15:53:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Also even assuming that indexation in iterators is something good this particular commit is bad. Imagine what will happen if I try to evaluate 123.repeat()[0]'}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2015-11-12 11:51:46.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add indexer to iterable objects

Most common use case is using `[]` operator after
some query function. Such function returns iterable object,
which will be passed to `[]` as argument,
so it isn't possible to find correct overload for this operator.
See tests for example.

Change-Id: I1d87d8eac24720081a71e6663403fe37e785c994
Closes-Bug: #1503269

Blueprint to use libvirt storage pools

This blueprint proposes using libvirt storage pools and
volumes for the libvirt images backends.

Spec for blueprint use-libvirt-storage-pools

Previously-Approved: Kilo

commit_message:
Check acpi_event fact only on CentOS 6

/proc/acpi/event has been deprecated in modern Linux kernel releases,
making the conditional evaluate to false on CentOS 7.

Closes-bug: 1514817
Change-Id: I95c1f0be8cc91f0ac45b3d93d0e991c7cb802442

[{'created': '2015-11-04 11:22:40.000000000', 'message': 'Set default stop timeout for pcmk services to 90s

This change will increase the default stop timeout for all the
pcmk services (non-ocf) to 90s

More info at: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1275324

Change-Id: I04f691396a4118b456728a43d71d32ac9a556431
'}, {'created': '2015-11-10 15:55:31.000000000', 'message': 'Set default start/stop timeout for pcmk services to 95s

This change will increase the default start/stop timeout for all
the non-ocf pcmk services to 95s to make sure it allows for at
least 90s to the systemd script to complete the start/stop.

More info at: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1275324

Change-Id: I04f691396a4118b456728a43d71d32ac9a556431
'}]
commit_message:
Set default start/stop timeout for pcmk services to 95s

This change will increase the default start/stop timeout for all
the non-ocf pcmk services to 95s to make sure it allows for at
least 90s to the systemd script to complete the start/stop.

More info at: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1275324

Change-Id: I04f691396a4118b456728a43d71d32ac9a556431

commit_message:
Add python 3 support

Use six versions of StringIO, urllib and raw_input
Use BytesIO instead of StringIO, where relevant
Added ability to distinguish binary and non-binary modes in utils.File
Use six.b for lyterals where relevant
Use six.iteritems, where relevant

Targets blueprint: client-py34-support

Depends-On: Id0e92840eb896ed487aafdcc39074aedefb55dda
Change-Id: I78a914cd77da7263d2bd0f871b8a478b5adadaee

commit_message:
Fix --retries option to kolla-build

Off by one error made the --retries option control the number of tries
rather than the number of retries.

Closes-Bug: #1514730
backport: Liberty

Change-Id: I976a8bb9e489d226f44926a6562d4d2af5de099c

commit_message:
Add whole disk image creation command to Installation Guide

Installation Guide lacks whole disk user image creation guidelines.
To use agent drivers, we should use images created with the parameter
"vm", like: "disk-image-create ubuntu vm dhcp-all-interfaces -o my-image".

Change-Id: I82c30c20a1e1280beb8d30bfd3dd12df917172cb
Co-Authored-By: Lilia Sampaio <liliars@lsd.​ufcg.​edu.​br>
Closes-Bug: #1514955

commit_message:
Make api-paste.ini config optional

* osprofiler.web.WsgiMiddleware now treats hmac_keys as optional arg
* add hmac_keys argument to enable() method to use it later in
  OpenStack services setup

Change-Id: Ib544d2732c7307bc5405b4336eda80120d2f43af

    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to

    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

Why?
Our policy tries to not install third party software. That's weird Nuage plugin is not packaging in UCA or RDO, that means they are not mainstream which is something we try to avoid to support in our Puppet modules."}, {'account_id': 8239, 'date': '2015-10-16 16:42:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

> Why? Our policy tries to not install third party software. That's weird Nuage plugin is not packaging in UCA or RDO, that means they are not mainstream which is something we try to avoid to support in our Puppet modules.

Nuage plugin could be packaged in RDO (and was in Juno), but we need to provide other Nuage components as RPMs, which cannot be packaged in RDO.  Given that, it's more consistent to provide a single repository and set of packages including all Nuage components.

The primary purpose of this Puppet work is to integrate with RDO Manager and OSP Director."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-10-19 14:00:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: Code-Review-1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-19 21:12:22.000000000', 'message': 'This changelist introduces support for Nuage Neutron plugin configration
and Nuage VRS configuration. The associated spec tests and custom types and providers
have also been added. This follows the same pattern as other plugins such as midonet and
opencontrail.

Change-Id: I0f092bf437739cac0b328822022e932fe5d1c6f2
'}, {'created': '2015-08-19 21:39:48.000000000', 'message': 'Support for Nuage Neutron plugin configration and Nuage VRS configuration in puppet-neutron.

* manifests/plugins/nuage.pp
  ** Nuage Neutron plugin is a monolithic Neutron plugin (core_plugin in neutron.conf can be set to nuage).
  ** The plugin.ini file for the Nuage Neutron plugin needs to be created with correct properties for the Neutron service to come up (configured in manifests/plugins/nuage.pp).
  ** The NuageNetlib is a component that is associated with the Nuage Neutron plugin and needs to exist for the Neutron service to come up (this check is made in the manifests/plugins/nuage.pp file)
  ** To add the configuration parameters to the plugin.ini file a custom resource type has been created (neutron_plugins_nuage).
* manifests/agents/nuage.pp
  ** The Nuage VRS is based on OVS and is installed on the compute nodes. The Nuage Neutron plugin, Nuage Netlib and VRS are part of the same solution. The Nuage VRS needs the active_controller and backup_controller (OpenFlow controller) to be set correctly in the /etc/default/openvswitch file. This is accomplished using the /manifests/agents/nuage.pp file.
* init.pp
  ** Just comment addition that core_plugin=nuage is now supported by puppet-neutron
* params.pp
  ** Parameterizing names of Nuage Netlib and Nuage Neutron Plugin (pattern based on existing midonet code)
* config.pp
  ** Call to create_resource similar to other plugins
* Spec tests
  ** spec tests for the plugin/nuage.pp and agents/nuage.pp

The associated spec tests and custom types and providers
have also been added. This follows the same pattern as other plugins such as midonet and
opencontrail.

Change-Id: I0f092bf437739cac0b328822022e932fe5d1c6f2

'}, {'created': '2015-09-23 17:19:25.000000000', 'message': 'Support for Nuage Neutron plugin and Nuage VRS in puppet-neutron

* manifests/plugins/nuage.pp
  ** Nuage Neutron plugin is a monolithic Neutron plugin (core_plugin in
     neutron.conf can be set to nuage).
  ** The plugin.ini file for the Nuage Neutron plugin needs to be created
     with correct properties for the Neutron service to come up
     (configured in manifests/plugins/nuage.pp).
  ** The NuageNetlib is a component that is associated with the Nuage
     Neutron plugin and needs to exist for the Neutron service to come up
     (this check is made in the manifests/plugins/nuage.pp file)
  ** To add the configuration parameters to the plugin.ini file a custom
     resource type has been created (neutron_plugins_nuage).
* manifests/agents/nuage.pp
  ** The Nuage VRS is based on OVS and is installed on the compute nodes.
     The Nuage Neutron plugin, Nuage Netlib and VRS are part of the same
     solution. The Nuage VRS needs the active_controller and
     backup_controller (OpenFlow controller) to be set correctly in the
     /etc/default/openvswitch file. This is accomplished using the
     /manifests/agents/nuage.pp file.
     This is based on existing model of ml2 agent creating the
     br-int and br-tun bridges and n1kv setting the parameters
     needed by n1kvem.
* init.pp
  ** Just comment addition that core_plugin=nuage is now supported
     by puppet-neutron
* params.pp
  ** Parameterizing names of Nuage Netlib and Nuage Neutron Plugin
     (pattern based on existing midonet code)
* config.pp
  ** Call to create_resource similar to other plugins
* Spec tests
  ** spec tests for the plugin/nuage.pp and agents/nuage.pp

The associated spec tests and custom types and providers
have also been added. This follows the same pattern as other plugins
such as midonet and opencontrail.

Change-Id: I0f092bf437739cac0b328822022e932fe5d1c6f2

commit_message:
Support for Nuage Neutron plugin in puppet-neutron

* manifests/plugins/nuage.pp
  ** Nuage Neutron plugin is a monolithic Neutron plugin (core_plugin in
     neutron.conf can be set to nuage).
  ** The plugin.ini file for the Nuage Neutron plugin needs to be created
     with correct properties for the Neutron service to come up
     (configured in manifests/plugins/nuage.pp).
  ** To add the configuration parameters to the plugin.ini file a custom
     resource type has been created (neutron_plugins_nuage).
* init.pp
  ** Just comment addition that core_plugin=nuage is now supported
     by puppet-neutron
* params.pp
  ** Parameterizing names of Nuage Neutron Plugin
     (pattern based on existing midonet code)
* config.pp
  ** Call to create_resource similar to other plugins
* Spec tests
  ** spec tests for the plugin/nuage.pp

The associated spec tests and custom types and providers
have also been added. This follows the same pattern as other plugins
such as midonet and opencontrail.

Change-Id: I0f092bf437739cac0b328822022e932fe5d1c6f2

(1 comment)

The vagrantfile is becoming more and more complex as we keep adding support for different boxes or new config options. I'm not questioning the need for a new ubuntu box, as long as we all agree it's supported as "best effort", in other words "I'm not using it, I probably won't realize when it breaks, people using it will need to submit a patch".
I'm more concerned about all the config options we keep adding to the vagrantfile especially since this file is version controlled. I'll try to implement a better way to configure the vagrant setup.

The code is looking good otherwise.

Ideally I prefer to have separate commits for each logical change:
- add jetbrains files to gitignore
- node settings
- ubuntu support

It's not a big deal this time, but please try to keep it in mind next time you submit a change.

I'm only +1 now because I'd like your feedback on the registry version.'}, {'account_id': 19148, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:27:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 19148, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:37:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I agree with that statement Martin.
One of the biggest issues I found while trying to set up kolla was the dependency requirements of certain libraries and versions. The documentation I found on the internet in some cases was outdated and I had to go on a trial an error basis.
If we could take a configuration driven approach and centralized the list of libraries and which versions have been tested and approved it would make a lot easier to maintain support for different boxes.
As far as the Vagrantfile I think that by breaking the AIO and multi-node set up into different modules it could be easier to change one without introducing bugs into the other.
Just some thoughts.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-11 17:33:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Added Ubuntu support for Vagrant

Added support for Vagrant VirtualBox provider to
provision an Ubuntu VM to run kolla. A new
bootstrap-ubuntu.sh script has been created which
provisions the Ubuntu VM with all kolla depdencies
including docker 1.8.2, ansible 1.9.6 and python-tools
Also created vars in the Vagrantfile to define the cpu and memory settings of the
VM nodes used to run kolla

DocImpact

Change-Id: I4609d7f577e948b04663901afd0c5d1d154c8ac4
Implements: blueprint vagrant-ubuntu-support

commit_message:
UI: Task & Execution screen refactored

* enhanced django template inheritance
* removed redundant template (html) files
* added link to task overview from execution overview
* when clicking task under execution main table,
  it now opens under task menu, which handles the logic
* same as above - when clicking execution under main tasks table

Screenshots:
http://pasteboard.co/23xFix0r.png
http://pasteboard.co/23jzE8JJ.png

Partially implements blueprint:tasks-screen-improvments
Partially implements blueprint: mistral-dashboard-executions-screen

Change-Id: Ibb4a8814b421b5dffcff264e7517a3b3ba29fdd7

commit_message:
Move the mariadb expect code to a script

Atleast in a script, sudo can be made to only allow the script to
run from the mysql process in the future, versus all the proceesses
being able to be executed as root presently.

Change-Id: I030b57086e37e4dc8f668f98c04335d94ab9d2b0
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
Drop root for Horizon service

Drop root privileges for Horizon service.  It is necesssary to set
a capability on the filesystem to allow binding to port 80 as a
non-root user.  I have tested this works correctly from a registry
on both CentOS and Ubuntu.

Change-Id: I4c26f28bb28b6633784e6842f3423a2425332c27
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
Fix vagrant libvirt proxy support

The libvirt driver for Vagrant currently tries to install rsync plus a
few other things before the bootstrap which it cannot do without a
proxy.

This commit adds doc and sample config for the vagrant-proxyconf plugin,
which handles proxies in a better way throughout. This also allows us to
fix up the docker proxy, both for the daemon's connection to dockerhub
and the build.

Change-Id: I06f905b60d58c0857bafa4e20ee2460a6ed6c2fb
Closes-Bug: #1514871

commit_message:
Change default bond-mode

The default balance-tcp is causing issues with deployments.
Defaulting to active-backup.

After ~ 100 guests (total) connectivity to each guest would become spotty
(simple pings would fail, then become successful.) In /var/log/messages
we saw :
"overcloud-controller-1 kernel: openvswitch: ovs-system: deferred action
limit reached, drop recirc action"

For more details, refer to this link:
http://openvswitch.org/pipermail/discuss/2015-October/019168.html

Change-Id: Ia0f2592a289e13472b98d97057cd516c5048fe59

Fix repo path for tempest-plugin-cookiecutter

commit_message:
Add tox.ini to be able to run tests

In addition to the tox.ini, there are some more changes
to enable testing:

- require flake8 in test-requirements.txt
- fix current pep8 errors
- add .gitignore including the .tox dir

Change-Id: I4cf9d8fc1c9a2eb4929fddb4a18a7db87481017c

commit_message:
Drop tag pushing rights from ironic-inspector-release

ironic-inspector is release:managed now, we need to allow the release
team to make releases instead of us.

Change-Id: I667535ffafbbc9bad7bd7f46433c0ba4db2df3cf

commit_message:
Ironic: Create and enable pxe_ipa-ipxe-nv in ironic

This patch is adding a non-voting job to test Ironic booting iPXE. iPXE
setting up iPXE is already supported in DevStack.

Change-Id: I41d31588f0c1bd6c1154bb9c7e56391ed614d67e

commit_message:
Only run releasenotes jobs if needed

Only run the release notes jobs if anything in releasenotes directory,
the requirements files or tox.ini gets updated. There's no need to run
these jobs if other changes are done.

Change-Id: I40296f6c5960a49377ecbe6620dcc2eaa0b10b42

commit_message:
Fixing /etc/rabbitmq permission bug

A change from the "Remove dir_mode from rabbit key distribution" commit caused
a bug where non-primary RabbitMQ containers would keep /etc/rabbitmq
permissions set to 0750 (the default is 0755).  This prevented the plugins
file from being read and it broke queue mirroring.

This patch ensures that the default permission of 0755 is set on RabbitMQ
and should prevent problems with future upgrades.

Closes-bug: 1513668

Change-Id: I62d6b09dad0eef0d9543442bb727f6c946d8738e
(cherry picked from commit 5862d0e894429929062119016517bddb88fb17a1)

commit_message:
Set STABLE_RELEASE based on ZUUL branch variables

OVERRIDE_ZUUL_BRANCH is set for stable periodic jobs

ZUUL_BRANCH will be stable/liberty for changes proposed
from those branches.

commit_message:
carbonara: fix exception when creating metric

_create_metric() never returns MetricDoesNotExist, which makes no sense.
But it can raise MetricAlreadyExists.

Now, the way we use this function is always inside a lock that is tied
to the metric, so it's impossible that this exception is raised in
theory – and we never saw it so far in practice.

But still, for the sake of it, let's fix that mistake!

'}, {'created': '2015-11-10 15:11:16.000000000', 'message': "Add test with assigning controllers to non-default nodegroup

1. Revert snapshot with ready master node
2. Create environment with Neutron VXLAN and custom nodegroup
3. Configure its networks: floating ranges and ALL VIPs must be
   from networks which belong to 'custom' nodegroup. Set IPs for
   VIPs: use the same subnet, but change addresses automatically
   assigned by Nailgun.
4. Bootstrap slaves from custom nodegroup
5. Bootstrap slave nodes from default nodegroup
6. Add 3 nodes from 'custom' nodegroup as controllers
   Add 2 nodes from 'default' nodegroup as computes
   Add 2 nodes from 'default' nodegroup as cinder
7. Run network verification
8. Deploy environment
9. Run network verification
10. Run OSTF

Change-Id: I3b6db9a1ca0c98444998ad05353a03efc8243c71

commit_message:
Add test with assigning controllers to non-default nodegroup

Scenario:
1. Revert snapshot with ready master node
2. Create environment with Neutron VXLAN and custom nodegroup
3. Configure network floating ranges to use public network
   from custom nodegroup
4. Bootstrap slaves from custom nodegroup
5. Bootstrap slave nodes from default nodegroup
6. Add 3 nodes from 'custom' nodegroup as controllers
   Add 2 nodes from 'default' nodegroup as compute and cinder
7. Run network verification
8. Check addresses allocated for VIPs belong to networks
   from custom nodegroup
9. Deploy environment
10. Run network verification
11. Run OSTF

Change-Id: I3b6db9a1ca0c98444998ad05353a03efc8243c71
Implements: blueprint test-custom-nodegroup-controllers

commit_message:
Remove eventlet usage

This entirely removes the eventlet usage. We do not monkey patch
anything anymore.
As far as messaging is concerned, what's used now is the threading
executor.

Change-Id: I42416e05671ef766ca2a8b326d84e7664e14de7d

commit_message:
Run project-config-compare-xml on jenkins/jobs only

Another optimization to help reduce check / gate pressure. This job
would only have needed to be run 86 out of 200 times.

Change-Id: I648f13eaea9ce003d6ee67d7ce4b1438f78d8a62
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Use separated ACL groups for sahara-dashboard

We'll be working on moving Sahara related code from Horizon back
to the sahara-dashboard repo and so we'd like to have additional
core reviewers in this repo (in addition to sahara-core team).

Change-Id: I9b5dccb154a7dd2bce00ca172e0f4951b9e479ae

commit_message:
Revert "Remove TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in the api tox env"

This reverts commit a32e31a624cf5190ed267effed8f7db2c9919949.

We should be able to merge the revert back once tox project fixes the
bug* on their side.

* https://bitbucket.org/hpk42/tox/issues/285/tox-220-breaks-some-toxini-config-files

Change-Id: Ic1f5391c687b2683cbaab210c543022aa1f26e83
Related-Bug: #1515335

commit_message:
Remove useless job from python-muranoclient and make CLI job voting

- Remove gate-murano-devstack-dsvm from python-muranoclient repo due to
this job is useless. It install client not from commit, but from pypi.
- Make gate-muranoclient-dsvm-functional voting and add this job as
gate job for muranoclient.

Change-Id: I146a5627c640e2ae57437c68ec119489ca6b23f7

commit_message:
Enhance attach_detach_volume test

This patch adds the ability to attach & detach a volume to a server
multiple times in attach_detach_volume test, default of 2
('attach_detach_times' option in tempest.conf) will effectively test
attach, detach, re-attach.

Change-Id: I6628ed51e4f23ed9b194b4793027dec6f32b8062
Depends-On: I97e7be15855193427146efe0acd03ca0939214c1

commit_message:
Fix OCF scripts for ceilometer agents

Ceilometer central and compute agents were merged into
one polling agent during Kilo development cycle.
So, they were deprecated during kilo (and Fuel 7.0).
In Liberty those binaries were removed, that's why we
need to update our OCF scripts according to these changes.

Change-Id: I8b172aab9999f8c22c279f2bbc9213c0c9e808c7
Closes-bug: #1511763

I believe that is internal app issue and it has to be fixed on app level'}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2015-11-04 14:55:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

Understood now, that is not the app layer.
This patch looks correct for a single node. When we start up a rabbit node and do import - there are no connections. But auto-delete queues would have been removed anyway, but by the AMQP/rabbit broker implementation details, correct? IIRC, a-d queues removed automatically when no active connections?

While for the mirrored cluster things not so obvious. A-d queues may still have active connections on other nodes, right? And if they don't, these queues will be removed anyway (see above). So, the control plane may not make decisions here. It have no enough information. The AMQP cluster internal state should care about those a-d queues based on active connections."}, {'account_id': 7109, 'date': '2015-11-05 08:56:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Bogdan, regarding
>> IIRC, a-d queues removed automatically when no active connections?

It is almost correct, there is one caveat in AMQP reference guide: "If there was no consumer ever on the queue, it won't be deleted." (quoted from https://www.rabbitmq.com/amqp-0-9-1-reference.html#queue.declare.auto-delete)

That causes the problem when script recreates fanout queues which are not consumed anymore. Though nobody consume from them, they are connected to fanout exchanges and receive all messages coming to them.'}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2015-11-09 15:45:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I see. That is about the second part "A-d queues may still have active connections on other nodes"? How would this work with the script? Would it remove such queues making decision locally instead of cluster-wide?'}, {'account_id': 7109, 'date': '2015-11-09 17:13:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Uploading definitions file does not delete any entities. For example, if queue was not defined in uploaded definitions file, but was present in the cluster, then it will survive. I've just verified that on my setup - I've uploaded a definitions file with a single queue defined. All other queues, absent in defs file, survived the upload.

Please clarify if you meant something else."}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2015-11-12 08:48:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

thank you, it is clear now'}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2015-11-12 08:48:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-12 08:48:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

commit_message:
Clean rabbitmq dump of auto-delete queues

This change adds a script that can be used on the output from the
rabbitmq admin plugin that dumps the rabbitmq definitions to a json
format. This script removes the auto-delete queues and cleans up any
references to them in the bindings and exchanges.

Change-Id: Ie3f3194b3eaaa8dc28d1cd3442090b586e177306
Closes-Bug: #1497961
Co-Authored-By: Dmitry Mescheryakov <dmescheryakov@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Port quotas to core API

Changes:
- Register quota and quota class sets API as core API using old links.
- Remove extensions code for quota and quota class sets.
- Leave rename of API urls for future update which will be done with
  bump of microversion after port of all extensions to core API.

Partially implements bp ext-to-core

Change-Id: I642e6dc78fd908a4850afc61505dcf34d330acca

commit_message:
Fix race condition for /openstack directories

To resolve a possible race condition when containers are creating
log directories the /openstack directory and its basic sub-directories
are being created within the openstack_hosts role which will ensure that
the appropriate skeleton is available when the containers go to build
in subsequent tasks.

Closes-bug: #1426254
Change-Id: Icdbddf285f8b898518657b082a9263a2923c97c4
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Support print_list to print a list of dict

print_list can only print a list of objects. There is a need to
print a list of dicts.

Change-Id: I8c976f1d2950f9dcb67eeec3afc80a19a96d0f27

commit_message:
Add "unreleased" release notes page

We need a release notes page to show notes for unreleased versions by
scanning the "current" branch. This ensures that notes files cannot be
merged if they break the releasenotes job.

Change-Id: Ic0614c37a67ebd28d1da0c0947c69c753833c870
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Added CORS support to Manila

This adds the CORS support middleware to Manila, allowing a deployer
to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client may
break the single-origin policy and access the API directly.

For Manila, the paste.ini method of deploying the middleware was
chosen, because it needs to be able to annotate error responses
created by other middlewares. If one such middleware throws an
error - such as an auth error from keystone - that error response
must still have CORS headers in order to be readable by the
user agent.

OpenStack CrossProject Spec:
   http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/cors-support.html
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
OpenStack Cloud Admin Guide:
   http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/cross_project_cors.html

Change-Id: I9d4b6d0eb380da3eae3867fcebe30fdd5824978d

commit_message:
Add project-name/-id validation for the OSC "openstack quota set"

The quota info would be set into DB, even though the project actually
does not exist.
This patch tried to add a validation to forbid this undesirable behavior.

Change-Id: Ia2d8c96527820e25b074e6486d3f39c5ad7eae60
Closes-Bug: #1512638

commit_message:
Revert "Add Pillow to test-requirements.txt"

This reverts commit 47b401f9eb2a129eec11bf0f5428e00869e8ca57.

Adding Pillow to *requirements.txt was a temporary way to set the
upper bound to < 3.0.0

nodepool thick slaves and requirements have been fixed and devstack is
fixed in the patch that this depends on.

Conflicts:
	test-requirements.txt

Change-Id: I3fc4009680ace3ba9c222aa7ad8c8ff7d6794f94
Depends-On: I2bec8cf1bfeaaa6ae329704229fdeb86d26e55c7

commit_message:
Remove lib/neutron_plugins/ibm

SDN-VE on neutron is already removed.
This patch removes SDN-VE from devstack.

Ref.
  Removing the SDN-VE monolithic plugin
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/217703/
  Remove IBM SDN-VE left-overs
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/237716/

Change-Id: Ie1b531153d1632798235b1100cdf9b068edcce26

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-18 20:28:38.000000000', 'message': 'Update internal snat port prefix for multiple IPv6 subnets

In neutron when multiple IPv6 subnets on the same
network are added to a router interface, the router
interface port is updated with multiple fixed_ips rather
than creating a new port. In the case of IPv4 subnets
a new port is created for every added interface.

For dvr routers there are internal snat ports that are
created for every router interface that is added to a
router. So when multiple IPv6 subnets on the same network
was added to a dvr router, the internal snat ports were not
appended with the IPv6 prefix properly.

An error log message was thrown for the SNAT port not
matching the given internal port for the IPv6 address.

This patch will address this issue when IPv6 subnets are
added or removed from the dvr router that are on the
same network.

Partial Bug: #1493524

Change-Id: I777d95d9a148fc6b6bad4538f3a1156ae5052bf6

commit_message:
Update internal snat port prefix for multiple IPv6 subnets

In neutron when multiple IPv6 subnets on the same
network are added to a router interface, the router
interface port is updated with multiple fixed_ips rather
than creating a new port. In the case of IPv4 subnets
a new port is created for every added interface.

For dvr routers there are internal snat ports that are
created for every router interface that is added to a
router. So when multiple IPv6 subnets on the same network
was added to a dvr router, the internal snat ports were not
appended with the IPv6 prefix properly.

An error log message was thrown for the SNAT port not
matching the given internal port for the IPv6 address.

This patch will address this issue when IPv6 subnets are
added or removed from the dvr router that are on the
same network.

Partial-Bug: #1493524

Change-Id: I777d95d9a148fc6b6bad4538f3a1156ae5052bf6

commit_message:
Install kernel-modules package on fedora

Since f21 the kernel modules are split to multiple packages
and by default just the core modules gets installed.

nova requires iscsi_tcp module for attaching a volume
from any iscsi source (default cinder lvm setup).

On el7 it is not required.

Change-Id: I31705720ade5defd1b6d4b95bc51c2a11a5f0364
Related-Bug: #1429504

@Vilobh: Do you have use-case/needs for this change?  I thought Magnum will handle it at flavor (like nova/ironic) and template level.'}, {'account_id': 7049, 'date': '2015-10-19 08:27:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Egor, right now, server_type and templates have mapping.

For ironic (bm), it have ironic templates.
for (vm) it have vm templates.


Ideally, we hope one templates can deal with above cases. But sometimes, seems not. Especially ironic not have same feature support like VM.

I also have bp for this https://blueprints.launchpad.net/magnum/+spec/magnum-baremetal-full-support  I would bring it talk in summit. if possible.


For this fix, I think it is OK. But not needed to merge in liberty. It can be merged in M cycle.


As liberty better not include db scheme changes'}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-10-19 17:37:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Egor : If we can do that at flavor level then we might not need it. 

IMHO in order to distinguish it at the Flavor level won't the Flavor extra specs be populated with what kind of Flavor it as for example BM/VM ? 

Are you thinking along that direction ? Can you please explain in detail ? Thanks!

I agree with what Kennan has mentioned above."}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-10-20 05:22:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Vilobh/Kennan - thx for explanation, but I feel we have to many choices which may confuse everyone. E.g.
- image, has os_distro (usually people has different images for bm and vm, not always true (I know at lease one company which use the same image for both))
- ironic relay at flavors (I know several people who use it to differentiate between vm and bm, works fine)
- after introducing network model, we can add any key/value pair to baymodel. which can be ease used for bm vs vm differentiation

Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 12053, 'date': '2015-10-20 07:34:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2015-10-20 09:04:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I think the baymodel do not need to care vm or pm, this should leave to cluster operator to decide the baymodel will be used to create VM or PM with specified template, comments?'}, {'account_id': 7049, 'date': '2015-10-20 15:57:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)

Hi @Jay, for why baymodel here need vm or bm, because right now, one template can not work for both vm and bm.

We have different templates (vm and bm). so baymodel here vm or bm is just for mapping to different templates.[default baymodel have server_type == 'vm')


it was discussed use flavor to represent it. But it also has some drawbacks. Some discussion can be checked mail before, I think"}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-10-20 18:11:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Jay: +1, I agree. Operator should decide which model he wants to use for which use-case. And it shouldn't be just bm vs vm."}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-10-20 20:14:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Agree with Kennan one template can not work for both vm and bm and this option just specifies which particular template to use. If we don;t have such an option how does magnum know on which types of "node" to spin up containers on ? Node IMHO is an abstraction for VM/BM/PM etc and 

CLI => Template mapping is necessary.

@Egor : Even though operator need to decide which model he wants to use for which use-case but there should be a baymodel in existence before doing so. With this change we can enable that with the server_type option. The operator can specify a particular baymodel (which need not be restricted to bm/vm) and can be generalized to whatever platform which supports the "Node" abstraction. But for each server_type we need to have a corresponding template.'}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-10-20 20:22:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Vilobh: my concern is why sever_type, why not network_type for example (you never can predict what operator has in mind ;))'}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-10-20 20:27:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Egor : If naming is the question then its quite subjective IMHO isn't it ? 

We can update the documentation clearly specifying what does server_type stands for if that helps. Thoughts ?"}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-10-20 23:41:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Vilobh: sorry it wasn't about name ;). My point is that we are paying too much attention bm vs vm in our design. I think it's not a case for real live scenarios, e.g. we have use-case when template/deployment will be different based on flavor and network type. But it's my personal opinion and I really interested to hear different thoughts about this topic."}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2015-10-21 10:10:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Egor, after a second thought, I think that we can treat this as a temp solution now. Because now the magnum hard code VM in code when getting template and it cannot support BM now, we can have this parameter to enable end user can also use PM. What do you think? :-)'}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-10-22 04:17:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Jay:@Vilobh shared the link where it's used now (https://github.com/openstack/magnum/blob/master/magnum/conductor/handlers/bay_conductor.py#L65. If it's the case, lets call this property template_name/selector/etc instead. In this case advanced operator will change, but all others will use reasonable default (e.g. what we have now)."}, {'account_id': 7049, 'date': '2015-10-22 08:18:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Egor, we have server_type now, why need define another selector ?

do you suggest server_type change to selector ? I did not thinks that name is proper.'}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-10-22 17:41:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Kenan: we use server_type only for choosing right template. And I think we should rename it accordingly ("selector" just first name which come up in my mind :)). Otherwise it create confusion, e.g. operator want to select templates based environment name, but he still need to use "server_type" for this.'}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-10-22 17:51:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Egor : IMHO selector is not an apt name. selector is a pretty generic name.

What server_type gives you :-

1. Way to identify what kind of nodes on which you will spin up containers.

2. server_type (rather than selector) is more apt in saying whether a particular "Node" (the abstraction) is a VM/PM.

Naming as I said is a subjective question. Is there anything other than the name that's bothering you ?

HTH.'}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-10-23 06:05:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

@Vilobh: sorry, but I disagree. Template identify what kind of nodes cluster need as well as topology. I agree that names are always subjective, but lets try to move it to real functionality ;)'}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-10-23 06:07:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Vilobh: sorry, forgot ;). no objections about implementation, clean and straightforward ;)'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2015-11-01 00:26:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Egor and all, the server_type is the name that we selected after some discussion in dev list (The discussion lasted more than 2 weeks), can we go ahead with this name now?'}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-11-01 07:27:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Create BayModel with provided(VM/BM) server type

In its current state of art, the Baymodel is created
with only "VM" server type. This value is hardcoded in the
code and a tech debt bug was filed to clean it off. Also
this feature can be useful to allow bay model creation with
various server type like virtual machines, baremetal etc.

Client side changes will be provided as part of seperate
patch.

Partial-Bug: #1491003

Change-Id: I8981031d097fc41c94ad509c7b090f0a57a90525

commit_message:
[Swift] Add additional Swift scenarios

This patch adds additional swift scenarios to use what was created
during swift context.

Swift Scenarios:
- list_and_download_objects_in_containers
- list_objects_in_containers

Blueprint benchmark-scenarios-for-swift

Change-Id: I6d615889a1acfcd4686eb061f1041f5b22fd09f0

commit_message:
Remove Extra dashes in "missing argument" error

Running command `rally task report' having no default task uuid will
show error message with "----uuid".

Change-Id: I0336efec0ab297f6009f315ae5a8f43995cede13
Closes-bug: #1515309

commit_message:
Remove upper cap on Pillow

In Ieffd37f9d49b53c36da31916a6af4f3bfe11d411 we added a cap on Pillow as
Pillow 3.0.0 required additional C development headers to be present to
build.

Those binaries should be present since
I8da7dd95ae24cf06dc7bdc300fcf39947a6df093 merged.

Remove the upper cap now.

Depends-On: I2bec8cf1bfeaaa6ae329704229fdeb86d26e55c7
Change-Id: I881ad72e48a4da0a828706fcbbc51de7741db6c1

commit_message:
docs: Add more networking details to single interface section

Add complete localrcs, and also add a section for additional compute
nodes, to help demonstrate the OVS layout and how traffic flows over
VXLAN tunnels from compute nodes, to the L3 node, and out onto the
wire.

Closes-Bug: #1506733

Change-Id: Ibb5fd454bdcb8c13400c1e11f640c2aafc0f73ca

so this cluster bug fix is related to prepare timing out because of the directory being created? you are not creating this directory until its used by the configuration overrides? 

would it be possible for errors being hidden when the datastore starts up if this dir doesnt exist? because i would think its trying to query the dir for config files to import on start right?'}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:34:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Craig The 'overrides' directory has only files created and required by the Trove guest-agent. They should not be needed for the datastore to start (if it needs a directory to exist in order to start up at all it has to be initialized in the elements).

Although it's true that the current implementation initializes the directory earlier (in fact, too early), it would suffer the same issue - i.e. the datastore starts before the guest-agent - hence the directory would not exist anyway.

In summary, if a datastore needs an 'import' directory to exist it has to be created in the elements. The guest-agent will then write to that location. Otherwise, it does not need to be created until the GA starts writing first files into it."}, {'account_id': 4240, 'date': '2015-10-13 04:28:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Defer revision dir initialization in GA

GAs currently initialize their configuration directories right in the
service __init__. This is not necessary until the first configuration
changes get applied.
We have seen cases when the 'mkdir'/'chmod'/'chown' commands fail to
return within the 30s timeout limit on slow/heavily-loaded
(during cluster creation) machines.

This patch set defers the directory initialization until first overrides
get applied.

Change-Id: I67146d3c3e480f7e2200debbb79f91007e474c10
Closes-Bug: 1489948

Create pagination for the mistral client

Adding the ability to use pagination from the mistral client for list executions

Change-Id: Ie8cd3e3b10da0fc198553903341570d69fbb31b8

(cherry picked from commit ef58b731dcee00e0c20cc925afae42d5e3e6d690)

[{'created': '2015-05-01 23:52:35.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor Angular features enablement

To support stand settings service lookups, this creates
a common features area under local_settings.py and creates
common utility functions to access it.

Change-Id: I9a3ebb1d06d257b7b584adc556ec2872a01136d3
Partial-Bug: #1450940
'}, {'created': '2015-05-04 16:38:46.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor Angular features enablement

LAUNCH_INSTANCE_NG_ENABLED & LAUNCH_INSTANCE_LEGACY_ENABLED
were added as new feature toggles in Kilo. We added multiple
spots on the python code that looks it up in a rather non-declarative
and non abstract way. We also just created a generic settings
angular service. This worked, but now we are thinking about
ways to standardize on this concept so that a common features
API on the Python side and angular side can be used abstract
looking up whether or not a feature is enabled. This provides
better abstraction and isolation between code that needs to know
if a feature is enabled or not and will allow more standardization
or logic in the future to determine whether or not a feature is enabled
with less likelihood of having to rewrite all existing code.

This is not intended to replace all existing settings in settings.py.

Change-Id: I9a3ebb1d06d257b7b584adc556ec2872a01136d3
Partial-Bug: #1450940

commit_message:
Refactor Angular features enablement

LAUNCH_INSTANCE_NG_ENABLED & LAUNCH_INSTANCE_LEGACY_ENABLED
were added as new feature toggles in Kilo. We added multiple
spots on the python code that looks it up in a rather non-declarative
and non abstract way. We also just created a generic settings
angular service. This worked, but now we are thinking about
ways to standardize on this concept so that a common features
API on the Python side and angular side can be used abstract
looking up whether or not a feature is enabled. This provides
better abstraction and isolation between code that needs to know
if a feature is enabled or not and will allow more standardization
or logic in the future to determine whether or not a feature is enabled
with less likelihood of having to rewrite all existing code.

This is not intended to replace all existing settings in settings.py.

Change-Id: I9a3ebb1d06d257b7b584adc556ec2872a01136d3
Partial-Bug: #1450940

commit_message:
Validate nova server's metadata

This prevents "foo" getting passed into the metadata.
This can happen when using get_attr() to return a dynamic value.

Change-Id: I17eab659e65a51963e510add4d71fbc90a3a3a53
Closes-bug: #1338811

commit_message:
Add a new param for fernet tokens config

"revoke_id" param was added for fernet tokens
configuration. It revokes token by token identifier.
Setting revoke_by_id to true enables various forms
of enumerating tokens.

Change-Id: I645cd591f1018a9a595d8f738a782f64c0a984a4

commit_message:
Node's last_error to show the actual error from sync_power_state

When sync_power_state fails because of an exception the node's
last_error message wasn't showing what really happened to the node. This
patch is changing it so the actual exception message appears on the
last_error attribute making it easy to troubleshoot why the node was
put in maintenance mode by the conductor service.

Closes-Bug: #1508413
Change-Id: Ieeac3d13b80357fc7542f2387a552dc85ed7cd90

commit_message:
hz-page-header should allow string interpolations

As noted by Thai in his review for the patch
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/213879/, the hz-page-header
directive should be updated to allow string interpolations
such as {$ ... $} in order to support angular translate.

This patch can be tested by setting DISABLED = False in
_1051_project_ng_images_panel.py and _3031_identity_users_panel.py
and checking the header translation with the pseudo
translation tool.

Change-Id: If9778f361d2bb1682e258578b7525bb734b8f8b6
Closes-Bug: 1485778

commit_message:
tempest: use $::id fact for permissions

Instead of harcoding 'jenkins' user, use $::id fact so we can re-use
this manifest somewhere 'jenkins' user is not present.

Change-Id: I781e21112c3c0dfadd568f4d9436ddbd7d4a28b6

The change updates the logic within nova such to it will
now correctly set the management interface when using
a dynamic inventory without the container_networks options
within it.

This also updates the container create play so that it too
will properly skip a host that also may not have the container
networks entries within it's inventory configs.

Change-Id: I157a6ecd0ad99000369d786a649c7b40d791d917

commit_message:
Deployment fix when container_networks are not set

The change updates the logic within nova such to it will
now correctly set the management interface when using
a dynamic inventory without the container_networks options
within it.

This also updates the container create play so that it too
will properly skip a host that also may not have the container
networks entries within it's inventory configs.

Change-Id: I157a6ecd0ad99000369d786a649c7b40d791d917
Closes-Bug: #1508517
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Added unit tests for ringbuilder command-line utility

Added new unit tests:

test_add_device_old_missing_region
test_create_ring_number_of_arguments
test_add_duplicate_devices
test_rebalance_with_seed
test_set_overload_number_of_arguments
test_main_no_arguments
test_main_single_argument
test_main_with_safe

Modified existing unit tests to create sample ring at start of test.
This change was needed to have unit tests run correctly and demonstrate
code coverage.

test_unknown
test_search_device_number_of_arguments
test_list_parts_number_of_arguments
test_set_weight_number_of_arguments
test_set_info_number_of_arguments
test_remove_device_number_of_arguments
test_set_min_part_hours_number_of_arguments
test_set_replicas_number_of_arguments
test_set_replicas_invalid_value

Updates to handled nested mocks.
Updates to handle no exception case when SystemExit is expected.
PEP8 corrections.

Moved new tests from try blocks to use of assertRaises or call to
run_srb using exp_results with specified exit codes.

Updated run_srb to accept a dictionary of expected results. Specifically,
look for 'valid_exit_codes' to test, default to (0,1).

Change-Id: I4cf3f5f055a9babba140c68a9c7ff90b9c50ea62

"}, {'created': '2015-11-11 23:29:19.000000000', 'message': "Fixes missing testresource dependency

oslo.db made dependency changes that breaks us.

Change-Id: I3647189280115f708fac3301762e2ef57fad85e2
Closes-Bug: #1505327
(cherry picked from commit 4ffa5b64d877943deb83473fe5eb583636d1bb24)
(cherry picked from commit 0956619ad0973bcde786e2e4388c7c6801b1504b)

Get noop drivers to function within flows

The noop drivers suffered from not being updated and just not being tested
with being called within flows like normal real op drivers.  This gets the noop
drivers to succeed when called liked other drivers.  They do not do anything
and will return fake information whenever it is required they return data.
This can be improved later so that they actually do their own data store, but
that would require a much larger update and I'm not sure there's much value
in it.

commit_message:
Fixes missing testresource dependency

oslo.db made dependency changes that breaks us.

Change-Id: I3647189280115f708fac3301762e2ef57fad85e2
Closes-Bug: #1505327
(cherry picked from commit 4ffa5b64d877943deb83473fe5eb583636d1bb24)
(cherry picked from commit 0956619ad0973bcde786e2e4388c7c6801b1504b)

Get noop drivers to function within flows

The noop drivers suffered from not being updated and just not being tested
with being called within flows like normal real op drivers.  This gets the noop
drivers to succeed when called liked other drivers.  They do not do anything
and will return fake information whenever it is required they return data.
This can be improved later so that they actually do their own data store, but
that would require a much larger update and I'm not sure there's much value
in it.

Change-Id: I2627ed35c0f576f8cfa258b542e5bdb4be03dac8
Closes-Bug: #1501190
(cherry picked from commit 0c80a3bff14188ee6839c04b0ed931a5387c97d7)
(cherry picked from commit 98c1e9d2c76ac7fa64704bcd1c4faebbbf8108f2)

Filling the Importance field [1] with anything other than Wishlist for RFE bug reports
is wrong. People confuse priority with Severity (which is what the importance field is
about), and that can cause us some grief.

Therefore let's state clearly that from now on, RFE bug reports will be marked 'Wishlist'

"}]
commit_message:
Clarify that RFE bug reports should not have an importance set

Filling the Importance field [1] with anything other than Wishlist for RFE bug reports
is wrong. People confuse priority with Severity (which is what the importance field is
about), and that can cause us some grief.

Therefore let's state clearly that from now on, RFE bug reports will be marked 'Wishlist'
only.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Bugs#Importance

Change-Id: I4f12301e5d6b9b754efd456f0fb9da4e64555373

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Add development libraries needed by Pillow

Change I8da7dd95ae24cf06dc7bdc300fcf39947a6df093 added Pillow build deps
to nodepool thick slaves.  This means that Pillow 3 will work in unit
tests.

Make the matching change to allow Pillow 3.0.0 to work under devstack.

The longer term aim is to remove temporary upper cap.

Change-Id: I2bec8cf1bfeaaa6ae329704229fdeb86d26e55c7

commit_message:
Make sure template resource's metadata is refreshed

This copies the code snippet from instance.py, which refreshes
the metadata when we get a signal on a referenced resource.

Note: a functional test is coming in a later commit.

Closes-bug: 1418942
Change-Id: I5980c9cf4dc355b9bfa93273bc26a768ab9abdb8

commit_message:
Fix environment files parsing bug for stack-adopt

Should use process_multiple_environments_and_files
to parse the environment file arguments instead.

Change-Id: I2f00df78462f1468ff12f7f9f8ca8a5d4c2d181b
Closes-Bug: #1510818

commit_message:
Add Ansible testing infrastructure

The keypair test needed adjusting so that it would work in
the gating environment, and anywhere an SSH key may not be
available.

Change-Id: Ic9bf41c2b4041911d05217ad3748e097326bac3a

commit_message:
Centralize header parsing

All response headers are now exposed as unicode objects. Any
url-encoding is interpretted as UTF-8; if that causes decoding to fail,
the url-encoded form is returned.

As a result, deleting DLOs with unicode characters will no longer raise
UnicodeEncodeErrors under Python 2.

Related-Bug: #1431866
Change-Id: Idb111c5bf3ac1f5ccfa724b3f4ede8f37d5bfac4

commit_message:
Pass kwargs when using revoke_api.list_events()

The list_events method takes a keyword argument for last_fetch. One of the
tests in test_revoke.py was passing it as positional. I noticed this when
refactoring sql.DateTime formats out of the revocation events schema. This it
just a minor commit to fix it.

Change-Id: Ic62f2f2d928f7f09d98f12ce74bb2db7eae8f673

commit_message:
Delete kube-register

1. kubelet can automatically register nodes for us, so we don't need
to register nodes.
2. When we remove a node from the cluster, the nova instance is
terminated. So the instance has no stop process to run unregister
script. Heat has a spec [1] to add stop deletion policy now. After
this function is merged, I will add unregister script back.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/243012/

Change-Id: Id0ebef251f124e350dd25f1249887bc2ddbd4dd9
Closes-Bug: #1511570

2. make self.devices_with_udpated_sg_members just record the ACTIVE
   port, so when sg rules or members change, conntrack command for
   one ip_conntrack just exec one time.

Closes-bug: #1513765

Change-Id: Ib3bc260b745ff07652df7425d85479a33dfbbd70
